(375, 1, '2013-04-25 11:18:21', '2013-04-25 11:18:21', '<p>Facebook is easy, real friendship is not. Facebook is a lie. That''s why I quit.</p>\n\n<h1>Reasons To Quit Facebook</h1>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Real Friendships Take Real Effort</li>\n<li>Facebook Is Compulsive</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>My Objections to Quitting Facebook</p>\n\n<p>Other Objections to Quitting Facebook</p>\n\n<p>Do You Think Facebook Is Evil? What about Mark Zuckerberg?</p>\n\n<p>I wouldn''t call Mark Zuckerberg evil. He may be mistaken about a few things, just as I may be mistaken about a few things, but I believe he is a person created to be a reflection of God just like every other person.</p>\n\n<p>I do think Facebook is evil. That doesn''t mean I think anyone that works for Facebook is evil, or that using Facebook is evil. But any platform that''s success is based on people buying into lies is evil. </p>\n', 'Facebook is too easy, I quit!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-04-25 11:18:21', '2013-04-25 11:18:21', '', 372, 'http://josiahsprague.com/372-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(36, 1, '2009-05-21 20:08:19', '2009-05-21 20:08:19', 'Looking around on the internet, I''m finding some trends as far as what makes a website successful. This is my no means a definitive list, but rather a quick summary of some things that I am drawn to on the web and why I think these things are essential for a successful website. While many of my observations apply to websites in general, my specific focus will be on portfolio websites.\r\n<h2>Some Rules of Successful Design</h2>\r\nWhat makes a website successful is, first and foremost, it''s purpose. The purpose of a website is to communicate a message. The message needs to be clearly defined, and every aspect of the website should do it''s part to communicate that message. All of the aspects of a website are secondary to the message of the site.\r\n\r\nThe message of a portfolio website is, most likely, "Hire me!". This message should be made clear, and supported by the content of the site. A successful portfolio site will include examples of work to communicate the author''s skill, as well as a call to action encouraging visitors to consider hiring.\r\n\r\nSome supporting factors that make any website effective in communicating a message include; consistent navigation, usable search, standards compliance, up to date information and effective monetization.\r\n<h2>Some Things to Avoid</h2>\r\nIn light of a website''s message, anything that does not contribute to or enhance the message should be avoided. A feature may be a powerful communication tool on one website and completely out of place on another. For example, a discussion board may be a very useful tool on a social media website, but on a professional portfolio it may be out of place.\r\n\r\nOther things to avoid are unnecessary Flash animations, sounds that play automatically, and features that use large amounts of resources. These things can be used occasionally in the right places but to use them all the time is sort of like putting salt on everything you eat. Not everything needs it, and sometimes it''s better without.\r\n<h2>Good Examples</h2>\r\nThere is no shortage of good examples of portfolio websites.  DesignM.ag has a list of <a title="101 Awesome Portfolio Sites" href="http://designm.ag/inspiration/101-awesome-portfolio-sites/" target="_blank">101 Awesome Portfolio Sites.</a> The number one thing that I like about most of these portfolio sites is that they are standards compliant. It might not seem like a big deal, but standards compliance is the backbone of a successful site. Everything is built out of code, so if the code is healthy, it lends itself to a healthy site.\r\n\r\nThe first site on DesignM.ag''s list is <a title="Spoon Graphics" href="http://www.spoongraphics.co.uk/" target="_blank">Spoon Graphics</a>. Not only does the site look great, but it achieves its purpose effectively. The first thing a visitor to the site sees is the banner across the middle of the page explaining what the site is and offering links to find out more, view the portfolio or hire Chris, the owner of the site.\r\n\r\nAnother portfolio that stands out to me from the list is <a title="Design Disease" href="http://designdisease.com/" target="_blank">Design Disease</a>. The thing that draws me to this site is the creative design. The site incorporates an ocean theme while still maintaining a site that is easy to navigate. Design Disease also includes several other features that make it a successful portfolio including consistent navigation, usable search, standards compliance, up to date information and effective monetization.\r\n\r\nI especially like Design Disease''s natural approach to monetization. First by simply offering services for hire, but also by offering the services of other companies such as HostGator for web hosting. Many websites try to increase revenue by placing banner ads chosen by key word, but Design Disease simply makes a natural recommendation. Just as a side-note, this is where I see the future of advertising headed.\r\n<h2>Bad Examples</h2>\r\nPoorly designed portfolio sites are naturally harder to find, as they don''t get as much attention, but some of the worst of the worst can be found by doing a Google search for "worst website ever". There are some websites, which I generally dislike. These aren''t necessarily bad websites, but sites that I feel could do a much better job at communicating their message.\r\n\r\nHave a look at the introduction page on <a title="Scott Rockers'' Portfolio" href="http://rockerssoft.org/scott/" target="_blank">Scott Rockers'' Portfolio</a>. While I can appreciate the intent to make sure that visitors are aware that the site is Flash-based, the introduction page is an unnecessary step for most visitors that gets in the way of the message of the site. The best solution would be to avoid Flash unless it is absolutely necessary (most multimedia and animations can be handled with HTML, CSS and JavaScript these days). However, even when Flash is necessary the question of whether or not the visitor has Flash player installed can be addressed by the computer. Don''t make visitors do the work that your website should do for them. Include a script to skip the intro page if Flash is installed.\r\n\r\nOne last example is <a title="Eyes Go Dark" href="http://eyesgodark.com" target="_blank">Eyes Go Dark</a>. Eyes Go Dark is an example of a great message that is poorly communicated. When the site first loads, there is an introduction page with several external links. While external links are fine, it doesn''t make sense for them to be the first thing a visitor sees. That''s like visiting a house and being shown the way out as you enter. Skip the intro page and show visitors what they came for. Your message and your content should be right up front welcoming the visitors to your site.', 'Basic Principles of Website Design', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'basic-principles-of-website-design', '', '', '2014-03-02 19:48:50', '2014-03-02 19:48:50', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/?p=6', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(37, 1, '2009-09-14 21:37:00', '2009-09-14 21:37:00', 'Students at the University of Akron are getting excited about church. Campus Focus is the second largest student organization at the University of Akron and growing in size. While many churches are losing attendance from the college age crowd, Campus Focus is growing.\n\nMany college students imagine church is about old people wearing their Sunday best and singing hymns, but students at Campus Focus are interested in something different. Brian Kunkler, the pastor at Campus Focus, explains what Campus Focus is about to a group of students,\n<blockquote>The God that we follow around here has a bigger vision for your life than you have for your life. The God who lingers around here, whom we’re going to sing songs to in just a minute, has a bigger dream for your life than you have for your own life and He’s desperate to lead you in it. This is a high change environment.</blockquote>\nCampus Focus is a collection of college students, from many different backgrounds who have come together in the name of Jesus Christ. All are welcome, regardless of their current beliefs, gender, race, social status or lifestyle. But Brian concludes his speech to students with a warning;\n<blockquote>Look at what happened to people when they lingered around Jesus. Here’s a sampling from the four gospels. The blind see. The lame walk.  The oppressed set free. The outcasts are welcomed as family. The prostitutes become women of honor. The tax collectors become servants of the true king. Common fishermen become world changers. Swindlers and cheats pay back what they stole, and even get generous. The guilty get forgiven. The sin stain get cleansed. The proud get humbled and the self-righteous bow the knee. Wherever Jesus is, change is soon to follow.</blockquote>\nThe Campus Focus website, <a title="campusfocus.org" href="http://www.campusfocus.org" target="_blank">campusfocus.org </a>welcomes students to come to a weekly meeting at <a title="The Chapel in Akron" href="http://www.the-chapel.org" target="_blank">The Chapel in Akron</a> every Thursday night at 7:30 to see what they are all about. You can also find a weekly podcast from Campus Focus on the website.\n\nDISCLOSURE: Campus Focus is a student organization at <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu/" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a> of which I am an active participant. I was not paid to write this, however, it was written for a class that I am enrolled in this semester.', 'A High Change Environment', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-high-change-environment', '', '', '2014-03-02 19:48:50', '2014-03-02 19:48:50', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/?p=23', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(38, 1, '2009-09-15 22:03:15', '2009-09-15 22:03:15', 'There is often an awkward dynamic on the edge of urban college campuses where affluence meets poverty. <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a> is far from being an exception. It is a daily ritual on the edges of Akron''s campus; that awkward moment as a busy student passes a panhandler at a street corner or bus stop.\n\nSome hold signs, others tell stories. Some are visibly drunk or high, others are dirty. But the request is predictable; "My car ran out of gas around the corner. Can you help me out? I need a couple of bucks for a gas can...", "I haven''t eaten in two days and I''m hungry, do you have a ten so I can go get a pizza?", "My girl just left me with two kids and I''m just trying to get forty bucks to pay my electric bill."\n\nIt''s sad to see men and women in such distress. It evokes feelings of sympathy and a desire to help someone out. Yet helping these people often ends with the nagging thought that maybe giving money away to a stranger isn''t helping all that much. What if your sympathy is being taken advantage of? What if you''re actually feeding a person''s addiction and not the person? It''s hard not to wonder about the stranger''s motives.\n\nAccording to a <a title="Panhandling Brochurch [PDF]" href="http://www.downtownakron.com/_files/docs/panhandling-brochure.pdf">brochure</a> available from <a title="The Downtown Akron Partnership" href="http://downtownakron.com/" target="_blank">The Downtown Akron Partnership</a> most panhandlers are not homeless. In many cases, giving money to panhandlers  supports drug and alcohol addiction. Sometimes the best response is to just politely say no. Duane Crabbs, a street pastor of <a title="South Street Ministries Blog" href="http://southstreetministries.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">South Street Ministries</a> in Akron, says that when a person is struggling with addiction, almost anything you try to do for them is enabling their addiction.\n\nSympathy towards those in need is an appropriate response, but students should be wise about their giving. A number of organizations exist in and around Akron to help those in need. Students interested in giving can give to a local organization and when encountering a person in need, students can help by directing them to the appropriate organization. Students can refer to the <a title="Akron Street Card [PDF]" href="http://www.cvmsummit.net/Street%20Card%202009.pdf" target="_blank">Akron Street Card</a> for  a list of resources for those on the streets in Akron. The street card includes information about hundreds of organizations that can help with things from emergencies, to paying utilities, to getting fed and finding work.\n\nBut according to the <a title="The Haven of Rest" href="http://www.havenofrest.org" target="_blank">Haven of Rest</a>, sometimes what panhandlers truly lack is not money but bonds with others;  what many people are suffering from is a "profound disconnection from other people and institutions". Ryan Wells, a nursing student at the University of Akron, decided to face this need head on and get to know one of the panhandlers on campus;\n<blockquote>I’ve had the opportunity to get to know a gentleman who has been out of work for almost a year now. He’s got a place to crash, but no steady income, no stability. And after getting to know him, a lot of my hesitations proved true. Drugs were involved, alcohol too. But I’ve gotten to know and appreciate this man’s struggle. I can’t stress the importance of simply learning their story. Where are they at physically? Emotionally? Mentally? Spiritually? How are you really going to effectively help anyone without learning why they are the way they are? And I’ve found companionship and communication have served this man so much better than a 10-spot and a Tornado Burrito from Speedway ever could.</blockquote>\nPanhandlers are people with the same basic needs as anyone else. Don''t be afraid to get to know a panhandler. Ask them about their story. You may be surprised at what you gain from getting to know them, and they gain a friend in return. A good place to start is lunch in a public place. Not to feed them, but to sit down with them and get to know them.\n\nDISCLOSURE: This was written for a class I am enrolled in at <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu/" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a>. Duane Crabbs is the pastor of a church which I regularly attend, and Ryan Wells is a personal friend.\n\nSome other interesting reads that I came across while brainstorming for this post:\n\n<a title="Christians and the ''Art'' of Panhandling" href="http://www.boundlessline.org/2009/07/christians-and-the-art-of-panhandling.html" target="_blank">Christians and the ''Art'' of Panhandling - Boundless Line</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/article1015963.ece#" target="_blank">Panhandlers Strategies - St Petersburg Times</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.seattlepi.com/local/328421_beggar21.html" target="_blank">How Do Panhandlers Spend Your Money? - Seattle P.I.</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.internetmonk.com/archive/question-should-i-give-money-to-people-on-the-street-who-ask-for-it" target="_blank">Should I Give Money To People On The Street Who Ask For It? - Internet Monk</a>\n\n<em> </em>', 'Student, Meet Panhandler', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'student-meet-panhandler', '', '', '2014-03-02 19:48:50', '2014-03-02 19:48:50', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/?p=28', 0, 'post', '', 0);
