(136, 1, '2009-11-06 17:33:49', '2009-11-06 17:33:49', 'I was reading through the headlines of the latest Zipmail, and I saw one that said "Tired of Seeing the Homeless on the Streets?". The headline grabbed my attention, which I''m sure was the intended effect. But my first impression was more along the lines of "Tired of Seeing the Homeless?" and it made me kind of mad- just because someone is homeless doesn''t make them any less valuable. I see people devalue the homeless all the time and that attitude really gets under my skin. But I read the article, and I found that this wasn''t the attitude at all. The key word of the headline is "streets". Are you tired of seeing that people are forced to live on the streets? Then do something about it.\n<blockquote>Then come and help prepare the Haven of Rest Shelter to give them a place to stay. ZPN will be hosting a Community Outreach event at the Haven of Rest on Saturday, November 14th from 9:00am - 12:00pm. Only you can help keep them off of the streets and provide for them a warm, clean place to stay while making yourself feel better about your community.\n\nContact Information: Adam Myser zpncommunity@uakron.edu 330-972-7014\n\nSponsored by: Zips Programming Network</blockquote>\nThanks ZPN!', 'Tired of Seeing the Homeless on the Streets?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'tired-of-seeing-the-homeless-on-the-streets', '', '', '2014-03-03 00:34:18', '2014-03-03 00:34:18', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/?p=136', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(138, 1, '2012-07-12 17:35:49', '2012-07-12 17:35:49', 'For a good portion of my life, I''ve had an ambition to be a leader. That is not to claim that I''m necessarily gifted at being a leader, just that I have a natural desire to lead rather than follow, and that my desire to lead has been affirmed by those around me since I was a child.\r\n\r\nIn the past few years, since graduating college and beginning to form my career, my leadership ambition has focused on wanting to be a great web developer. I''ve been incredibly inspired by people such as <a href="http://chriscoyier.net/">Chris Coyier</a>, <a href="http://meyerweb.com/">Eric Meyer</a>, <a href="http://lea.verou.me/">Lea Verou</a> and <a href="http://paulirish.com/">Paul Irish</a>. I''ve paid attention to their leadership styles and spent a lot of time reflecting on how I can emulate their success while bringing my own originality into my career.\r\n\r\nI''ve thought about teaching, speaking, writing plugins, and blogging. I''ve thought about all the ways I''d like to inspire others to build great things on the web. And I''ve acted on none of them. Instead, in less than two weeks, I''ll find myself on a plane, bound for the mountain town of Jarabacoa in the Dominican Republic. I am so excited for <a href="/">what I''ll be doing at Doulos</a>, but the opportunity cost of this decision, is that I won''t likely be emulating the careers of any of the web folks who have inspired me over the past few years.\r\n\r\nThis morning I was reading a book that my stepmother gave me about leadership, <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Humilitas-Lost-Life-Love-Leadership/dp/0310328624">Humilitas - A Lost Key to Life, Love and Leadership</a>, contemplating my role at <a href="http://www.doulosdiscovery.org/">Doulos</a>, and reflecting on my recent ambition to be a leader in the web world. I was struggling to find a connection between my career ambitions and the career path that lies ahead of me. But I also read <a href="http://www.youversion.com/bible/1cor.1.niv">a letter</a> this morning that was written by a greek leader the Christian Church in the first century A.D. to his followers.\r\n\r\nHe reminded his followers that his purpose as a leader was "to preach the Gospel, not in cleverness of speech" lest Christ''s sacrifice be made void. And I was reminded, as I leave behind the career path that I''ve spent so much time pondering and seek an unconventional opportunity, that the purpose of my career is not to lead people to cleverness of web development, as I so often desire, but to lead people to Christ.', 'Thoughts on Leadership', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '17-revision-4', '', '', '2012-07-12 17:35:49', '2012-07-12 17:35:49', '', 17, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/17-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(139, 1, '2012-06-25 22:27:02', '2012-06-25 22:27:02', 'Dear Friends and Family,\r\n\r\nThis spring I have an opportunity to serve on a week-long mission trip to the Dominican Republic. On April 14-21, 2012, I will be going with a team from<a href="http://mosaicneo.com/">Mosaic church</a> in Stow, OH to <a href="http://www.doulosdiscovery.org/">Doulos Discovery School</a> in Jarobacoa. The mission of the school is “to educate and disciple servant leaders in the Dominican Republic”.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://josiahsprague.com/doulos/img/photo.jpg" class="polaroid" alt="Doulos Discovery School" />We will have the opportunity to help and encourage teachers during the most important and demanding week of their year, <a href="http://www.doulosdiscovery.org/expeditions.htm">expeditionary week</a>. We will be working alongside teachers and kids, finishing projects, testing students, and providing manual labor for other jobs around campus. We will also have the opportunity to work alongside students and teachers as they bring water filter systems and clean water education to the surrounding communities.\r\n\r\nThis will be an opportunity for us to share the love of Christ, and an experience that will impact my life and influence my ability to serve others with a greater understanding and capacity and I want to invite you to be a part of the whole process by praying for my team before we go, while we are there, and after the trip. I will be posting updates on Twitter (<a href="http://twitter.com/jo_Osiah">@jo_Osiah</a>) while we are there. I know God is doing great things, and I am excited that I get to be a part of what He is doing!\r\n\r\nIn order to go on this trip, I need to raise $1500 rather quickly. If you are willing to support me financially, any amount will go along way. You can donate online or, if you''d like your donation to be tax deductible, by <a href="#footnote">sending a check made out to Mosaic*</a>. You can also see <a href="#progress">my fundraising progress</a> at the bottom of this page.\r\n\r\nI take great joy in being surrounded by the body of Christ, and I believe, whatever we do for the Lord, we''re all working together. As your brother in Christ, I want to thank you for being a part of what God is doing with this trip. If you have any questions, please <a href="https://mail.google.com/mail/?view=cm&amp;fs=1&amp;tf=1&amp;to=josiah.sprague@gmail.com" target="_blank">contact me</a>!\r\n\r\nYour brother,\r\n<img src="http://josiahsprague.com/doulos/img/Signature.png" alt="Josiah Sprague" />\r\nJosiah Sprague\r\n\r\n<h2>My Fundraising Progress <small>I got everything I needed!</small></h2>\r\n<div id="progress" class="progress progress-striped">\r\n        <div class="bar" style="width: 100%;"></div>\r\n      </div>\r\n      \r\n     <form action="https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr" method="post">\r\n      <input type="hidden" name="cmd" value="_s-xclick">\r\n      <input type="hidden" name="hosted_button_id" value="VAYJ88UH398EE">\r\n      <input type="submit" class="btn btn-success btn-large" name="submit" value="Donate Now!">\r\n      <img alt="" border="0" src="https://www.paypalobjects.com/en_US/i/scr/pixel.gif" width="1" height="1">\r\n      </form>\r\n      \r\n     <p>\r\n            <small id="footnote"><span class="label label-important">Important!</span> *If you''d like your donation to be tax deductible, mail checks to PO Box 1687, Stow, Ohio 44224. Please do not write my name anywhere on the check, as this voids the tax deductibility of your donation. My name on the envelope will insure that the money is applied to the account established for this trip. A receipt will be mailed for all donations at the end of this calendar year.</small>\r\n      </p>', 'I''m going to the Dominican Republic!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-7', '', '', '2012-06-25 22:27:02', '2012-06-25 22:27:02', '', 6, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/6-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(141, 1, '2012-08-06 19:36:35', '2012-08-06 19:36:35', 'The last couple of weeks have been a whirlwind. Packing up my life in Ohio, saying my goodbyes, arriving in Jarabacoa and trying to get my bearings in a new country and culture has been challenging and exciting. There is so much going on, that it is hard for me to sit down in front of the computer to write, but I want to share what I''ve been doing with all of you. So here are my last two weeks, in pictures;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/1b0d5bbad57711e1bde812313b08e061_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-23" title="1b0d5bbad57711e1bde812313b08e061_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/1b0d5bbad57711e1bde812313b08e061_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Me, Dan and Danae" width="300" height="300" /></a> <a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/504f33e8d57711e18a5b22000a1cbb38_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-24" title="504f33e8d57711e18a5b22000a1cbb38_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/504f33e8d57711e18a5b22000a1cbb38_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Anginette getting ready to board the plane." width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nBright and early on the first day of my journey, I met up with Dan, Danae and Anginette at the Cleveland airport. Danae and I went to high school together at CVCA, and I am so blessed to be working with her and her husband Dan for the next three years. Dan will be the Expedition Coordinator at Doulos, and Danae will be the Instructional Coach for our teaching staff. Anginette went to CVCA as well, and just graduated this year. She will be at Doulos for the next semester to kick off her college career with Moody Bible Institute.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/a653d9c2df0611e1b62322000a1e8a75_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-25" title="a653d9c2df0611e1b62322000a1e8a75_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/a653d9c2df0611e1b62322000a1e8a75_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Guard tower in the parking lot." width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nOur flight was extremely smooth, and once we touched down in Santiago, we met with Tim, the Managing Director of Doulos, who drove us into Jarabacoa. On the way, we stopped to get groceries for dinner at La Sirena (the mermaid), which is more or less the Dominican version of WalMart. Parking lot security is taken very seriously here, and they have watchmen in towers to guard the cars.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/a8252022dc3f11e1979222000a1e8aa2_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-26" title="a8252022dc3f11e1979222000a1e8aa2_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/a8252022dc3f11e1979222000a1e8aa2_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Jarabacoa" width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis is Jarabacoa, our new home, seen from the mountains. You may be surprised, as I was, that pine trees are very common in the Dominican Republic. Another thing that is very common are the mosquitoes. Our first couple of days here, they couldn''t get enough of our fresh, North American blood. Insects are and lizards are the largest wild animals here. The scariest wildlife I''ve seen so far is a praying mantis, which is more amazing than scary. But some of the staff found a giant tarantula while cleaning out the school''s administration building.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/6ffe4c20dd5a11e1958512313d29ea2e_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-27" title="6ffe4c20dd5a11e1958512313d29ea2e_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/6ffe4c20dd5a11e1958512313d29ea2e_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Mosquitos" width="300" height="300" /></a> <a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/46386d94dab711e1bf341231380f8a12_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-28" title="46386d94dab711e1bf341231380f8a12_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/46386d94dab711e1bf341231380f8a12_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Praying Mantis" width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nSo far my schedule has been focused on learning Spanish (which is simultaneously exhilarating and exhausting), and work days at the school. A few of us spent a few hours shoveling gravel, for which our bodies are still punishing us, and I got to spend a lot of time carving wooden signs for some new classrooms. Building things with my hands was a nice change from a 9 to 5 office environment.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/50c3fefadde511e19fb4123138101461_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-29" title="50c3fefadde511e19fb4123138101461_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/50c3fefadde511e19fb4123138101461_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Carving signs for the new Doulos classrooms." width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere are other changes from my usual routine that have been a little harder to adjust to, such as how laundry is done here. Some people have fully automatic laundry, as in the states, but it is very common here to do laundry with a semi-automatic washer, and then dry it on the line. It takes more time and patience, and it''s not so compatible with my usual procrastination when it comes to laundry. Over time I think I will get used to it and value the extra time to think and pray.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/b77be87cdc1611e194a422000a1e8aa6_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-30" title="b77be87cdc1611e194a422000a1e8aa6_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/b77be87cdc1611e194a422000a1e8aa6_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Air drying laundry takes a long time." width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere have been both blessings and challenges so far, but by far the best moments I have had in the last few weeks were those of fellowship and worship. In a culture where I feel lost 95% of the time, it is an absolutely amazing sensation of solidarity to realize that we know the same loving father that takes care of all of our needs.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/ecebb50cda3911e1aeb3123138150f49_7.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-31" title="ecebb50cda3911e1aeb3123138150f49_7" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/ecebb50cda3911e1aeb3123138150f49_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Bi-cultural worship." width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe very though of His love brings rest in a time and place where everything takes intentional effort for me. But I am tired, if you''re one for praying, pray that I would spend more time resting in His love, seeking His presence and listening to and trusting His voice. I have worries, like whether I will be able to communicate well in Spanish, whether I will build strong relationships here, whether all of the support that I need will come in, and whether or not I will excel at my job here.\r\n\r\nTo be honest, I spend much less time trusting God than I should. But I am thankful that I am here, with all of my familiar surroundings and comfortable retreats removed, where God''s love is the only comfort that I know. It brings to mind a quote that my Grandma loves to remind me of;\r\n<blockquote>Even youths grow weary and tired,\r\nAnd vigorous young men stumble badly,\r\n\r\nYet those who wait for the LORD\r\nWill gain new strength;\r\nThey will mount up <em>with </em>wings like eagles,\r\nThey will run and not get tired,\r\nThey will walk and not become weary.</blockquote>\r\nThank you for your prayers and support! I am looking forward to hearing from you!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Starting Life in Jarabacoa', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '22-revision-v1', '', '', '2012-08-06 19:36:35', '2012-08-06 19:36:35', '', 22, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/22-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(144, 1, '2012-08-30 14:47:45', '2012-08-30 14:47:45', '<blockquote>Consider it all joy, my brethren, when you encounter various trials, knowing that the testing of your faith produces endurance. And let endurance have its perfect result, so that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing. But if any of you lacks wisdom, let him ask of God, who gives to all generously and without reproach, and it will be given to him. But he must ask in faith without any doubting, for the one who doubts is like the surf of the sea, driven and tossed by the wind.</blockquote>\r\nIn the last several weeks, since moving to Jarabacoa, my faith has been tested by trials in various aspects of my life. I''m used to being in control of my relationships with others, my responsibilities, my income, and my abilities, but all of those things have been out of my hands in recent weeks. At times I have felt vulnerable to being tossed like a wave in the wind.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_145" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/14479712e8b611e1a74f1231380fcc36_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-145" title="Wave at Cabarete" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/14479712e8b611e1a74f1231380fcc36_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Wave at Cabarete" width="300" height="300" /></a> A wave being tossed in the wind at Cabarete.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThough the wind and waves of my life have been unpredictable lately, I have found incredible peace and security in talking to God about my worries and trusting that <a href="http://bible.us/rom8.28.nasb">He will work all things out for my good</a>. When we trust God, we can ride the wind and the waves with confidence, like the surfers that I saw recently in Cabarete. I know that no matter what direction the winds of life blow, God is in control. Even the trials are used to refine and build my character.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_146" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/edb01d50e8a011e1bf7c22000a1e9ddc_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-146" title="Wind Surfers in Cabarete" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/edb01d50e8a011e1bf7c22000a1e9ddc_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Wind Surfers in Cabarete" width="300" height="300" /></a> Surfers and Kite Boarders Riding the Wind and Waves in Cabarete[/caption]\r\n\r\nBut unless I am feasting daily on the truth of God''s word, I will be lacking the ability to trust God. It is easy for me to forget to <a href="http://bible.us/matt4.4.nasb">fill myself daily with God''s truth</a>. I remember so easily to feed my physical body. (And who wouldn''t with the delicious Dominican food that is so common here?), but it is so much more important for me to feed my spiritual body.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_147" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/bfddc0b4eeac11e1851d22000a1e9dc3_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-147" title="Fried Salami Sandwich with Tostones" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/bfddc0b4eeac11e1851d22000a1e9dc3_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Fried Salami Sandwich with Tostones" width="300" height="300" /></a> A common Dominican meal; A Fried Salami Sandwich with Tostones. One of my new favorites.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI am continuing to learn more and more every day about Dominican culture and language. Every conversation is a learning experience, and I am learning as much about communication itself as I am learning about my new home. What a beautiful thing that God has made us with the ability to communicate and share with one another, and it is so fulfilling when we<a href="http://www.relevantmagazine.com/life/whole-life/are-you-letting-others-define-you"> communicate in a way that honors God</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_148" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/64305cf2f03911e190bd22000a1cdd09_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-148" title="Learning to Make Chinola Tea" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/64305cf2f03911e190bd22000a1cdd09_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Learning to Make Chinola Tea" width="300" height="300" /></a> Learning to Make Chinola (Passion Fruit) Tea, Combined with a Lesson in Spanish[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_149" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/1cf9f6b8eeea11e1a4d022000a1d0cc7_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-149" title="Home in Jarabacoa" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/1cf9f6b8eeea11e1a4d022000a1d0cc7_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Home in Jarabacoa" width="300" height="300" /></a> The house where I am living. My current home.[/caption]\r\n\r\nGod is stretching me, and it is good. I am not comfortable, but I am able to rest in His love, and feel at home, confident that He is providing for all of my needs. I am so thankful for this time of growing in faith, and I am excited to see the fruits of this season of my life. Thank you for your continued prayers and <a href="http://josiahsprague.com/support/">support</a>!', 'God Is Stretching Me To Trust Him', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'god-is-stretching-me-to-trust-him', '', '', '2014-03-03 00:34:18', '2014-03-03 00:34:18', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/?p=144', 0, 'post', '', 1),
