(171, 1, '2012-10-15 14:20:21', '2012-10-15 14:20:21', 'A few weeks ago, I moved into a new house in Jarabacoa with two other roommates. My first couple of weeks here, I lived with a host family who were very generous and welcoming as I began my transition to living in Dominican culture. Living in this new house is allowing me to transition more into life and experiences here.\n\n[caption id="attachment_164" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/4bd7337c16ce11e291a022000a1e8839_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-164" title="My House" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/4bd7337c16ce11e291a022000a1e8839_7-300x300.jpg" alt="My House" width="300" height="300" /></a> I live in the house on the left with a red roof.[/caption]\n\nOne of the things that I am excited about living in my own apartment is the ability to host friends. It is common in Dominican culture to gather at friends'' houses, rather than going out together. Without having my own place where I could host friends, I felt that it was difficult to initiate or reciprocate friendships with Dominicans, but now, thankfully, I have that ability.\n\n[caption id="attachment_165" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/ae6bd4d80a6811e29f481231380fd1fd_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-165" title="Hanging out on the Porch" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/ae6bd4d80a6811e29f481231380fd1fd_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Hanging out on the Porch" width="300" height="300" /></a> Singing and playing guitar on my porch with Dominican and German friends.[/caption]\n\nHaving friends over to my house has given me more opportunities to learn Spanish, and  allowed me to experience Latin America''s famous dancing talent (and Gringos'' comparative lack of dancing talent) first hand. If you''re wondering why I''m not in this picture, you''ve obviously never seen me try to dance.\n\n[caption id="attachment_166" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/6b5099c40aa711e299b11231381b6f02_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-166" title="Friends Dancing" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/6b5099c40aa711e299b11231381b6f02_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Friends Dancing" width="300" height="300" /></a> My friends Steph and Natali dancing in my house.[/caption]\n\nI''ve also been able to take my experience with Dominican cuisine to the next level, now that I have my own kitchen in which to cook. I''ve learned how to cook yuca frita, salami, queso frito and tostones (all Dominican favorites) and I''ve discovered, surprisingly, that though they live in a country full of cheap avocados, most Dominicans have never heard of guacamole. Here, apparently, it''s a Gringo thing.\n\n[caption id="attachment_169" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/a4c42bc60e7611e2b52912313820446d_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-169" title="Burnt Tostones" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/a4c42bc60e7611e2b52912313820446d_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Burnt Tostones" width="300" height="300" /></a> My first attempt at Tostones. A little too crispy.[/caption]\n\nOne of the downsides of living in a new place is that it is farther from where I work, and I still haven''t been able to afford a motorcycle. The neighbor girls offered to let me use their "carro", but it''s not exactly my style.\n\n[caption id="attachment_167" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/1b4a04600e8f11e286fe22000a1de753_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-167" title="Neighbors" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/1b4a04600e8f11e286fe22000a1de753_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Neighbors" width="300" height="300" /></a> My neighbors showing me their homemade "carro".[/caption]\n\nI''ve been using my longboard to get to work. Though the streets are a little rough, it always provides a little bit of entertainment with the reactions I get from people on the street. This week, on my way home, a motorcycle taxi driver asked if he could try my longboard. He quickly attracted a crowd of people, and though he swore he knew what he was doing, I don''t think he ever rode a longboard before.\n\n[caption id="attachment_168" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/23672d5414ab11e2bf8b22000a1e8b2b_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-168" title="Concho Driver on Longboard" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/23672d5414ab11e2bf8b22000a1e8b2b_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Concho Driver on Longboard" width="300" height="300" /></a> A taxi driver on my longboard.[/caption]\n\nOf course, the longer commute isn''t all bad. It''s allowed me to explore more of Jarabacoa. I found that Batman apparently has a vacation home here.\n\n[caption id="attachment_170" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/f0145726085011e29035123138140023_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-170" title="Batmans House" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/f0145726085011e29035123138140023_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Batmans House" width="300" height="300" /></a> Batman''s Vacation Home[/caption]\n\nAnd when I finally get home from work, I can relax on my porch and enjoy the view. I definitely miss the beautiful fall weather in Ohio, but this view can definitely compete.\n\n[caption id="attachment_163" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/63671cdc13ea11e29a5322000a1d0353_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-163" title="Magote from Jarabacoa" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/63671cdc13ea11e29a5322000a1d0353_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Magote from Jarabacoa" width="300" height="300" /></a> The view from my porch in Jarabacoa[/caption]\n\nThank you all for your continued encouragement, prayers and support. Please stay in touch!', 'Moving into a New Neighborhood', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '161-revision-v1', '', '', '2012-10-15 14:20:21', '2012-10-15 14:20:21', '', 161, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/161-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
