(188, 1, '2012-11-20 14:21:06', '2012-11-20 14:21:06', 'A few weeks ago, many of us experienced hurricane Sandy. Here in Jarabacoa, it was hardly more than a rainy day. Many of my friends in Ohio were out of power for a few days, and friends on the east coast witnessed some flooding first hand. I don''t personally know anyone who was hit very hard by the storm, but I know very few people who weren''t on alert about it. Storms bring a lot of chaos and danger, and it is only normal to be on alert when a storm is coming in.\r\n\r\nI was reading a story yesterday about a group of fishermen who were caught in a storm. They had been attending a public speaking event near <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_of_Galilee">Lake Tiberias</a>, and afterward they set sail in a small group of boats with the man who had been speaking. Soon after they set out, they found themselves caught in an intense storm and their tiny boat began filling with water. The fishermen were all on alert, but the speaker of the event was <em>asleep in the midst of the chaotic storm</em>.\r\n\r\nStorms have woken many of us while we''re safe and secure in our houses. It seems hard to believe that this man would have been able to sleep through an intense storm in a little boat that was filling with water. It kind of makes you wonder what this guy''s deal was. Was he crazy, or what? I bet the fishermen who were with him in the boat were wondering the same thing. They were probably even a bit annoyed that he was sleeping instead of grabbing a pail or a rope and helping them to keep the boat from sinking.\r\n\r\nWhat happened next in the story is even harder to believe, but it explains exactly why this guy was able to sleep through the storm. The fishermen yelled at him to wake him up, "Dude, wake up! Don''t you care that this boat is sinking?!". The speaker woke up, and without saying a word to the fishermen, looked up at the sky and said, "Enough! Be calm!" and<em> the waves instantly stopped tossing, and the skies cleared up</em>. Then, he turned to the fishermen and said, "Why are you afraid? Don''t you know who controls the storms?".\r\n\r\nI''d imagine if any of us had experienced that, we would have been pretty freaked out. The fishermen, who were used to handling a boat on a stormy sea, were probably more freaked out by this guy than they were by the storm. I mean, <em>who IS this guy</em>? All he has to do is say a word and he can make a raging storm stop instantly. The real thing to fear is not the storms, but the guy who can control them.\r\n\r\nIf you haven''t caught on by now, there are <a title="Mark 4:35-41" href="http://bible.us/111/mrk.4.35-41.niv">three</a> <a title="Matthew 8:23-27" href="http://bible.us/111/mat.8.23-27.niv">historical</a> <a title="Luke 8:22-25" href="http://bible.us/111/luk.8.22-25.niv">accounts</a> of this story, and the people in the boat were Jesus and his disciples. This experience taught the disciples a clear lesson about who God is, and we can learn from it as well. We often have our own storms. The chaos and struggles of life threaten to drown us if we don''t stay on alert and work hard to keep things from going under. Sometimes the last thing we are able to do is to rest in the midst of the chaos of life.\r\n\r\nMy own life has felt very vulnerable to being overwhelmed by the wind and waves of life in the last several months. I''ve experienced the chaos of wondering where my paycheck will come from, driving on some crazy roads with some crazy Dominican drivers, not understanding the language of my neighbors and not knowing who I can trust or who is out to take advantage of a naive gringo. It can be hard to rest when you''re constantly fighting to stay afloat.\r\n\r\nBut this story can teach us how to rest in the midst of a storm. Jesus'' question to his disciples was, "Why are you afraid? Do you still have no faith?" The key to having peace in a storm is to know the one who sets it''s boundaries and stills it''s fury, and to fear Him more than we fear the raging waters around us.\r\n\r\nI have been learning to trust God more than I fear the storms. I still have a lot to learn, but I know that I can rest knowing that God sets the limits and that all of the raging storms in my life are stilled at His command. What about you? <em>What or who do you fear? Do you trust God more than you fear the storms? Are you able to sleep through storms?</em>', 'Sleeping Through Storms', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'sleeping-through-storms', '', '', '2014-03-03 00:34:18', '2014-03-03 00:34:18', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/?p=188', 0, 'post', '', 1),
