(193, 1, '2013-01-06 18:44:40', '2013-01-06 18:44:40', '&nbsp;\n\nOften, at Doulos, I get praise from others. People see me as a "good person", "a missionary", "a volunteer". At times, that sort of identity is easy to embrace. After all, who doesn''t want to be seen as a good person? I enjoy believing that I''ve earned it, that I''m a good guy, that I do good work, and that I''m faithful. But the problem with that is that it''s a lie. When I''m honest with myself about the things that I''m tempted by, and the things that I''m capable of, I see how dark my heart really is.  I love this quote;\n<blockquote>My memory is nearly gone;\nbut I remember two things;\nThat I am a great sinner, and\nthat Christ is a great Saviour.\n<cite>John Newton (1725-1807)</cite></blockquote>\nThese are my two greatest convictions in life. I hope that when I am old, and my memory begins to fade, or when I die and the memory of me begins in my friends and family, that these truths remain.\n\n<strong>I am a great sinner.</strong> Over the holiday break I was faced with temptations that are uglier than I wish to describe publicly. Every time I hear stories of a mass murder, a terrible rape, child abuse, marital infidelity, and other tragic events that are so obviously the action of a very sick person, I am aware that the seeds for such terrible actions exist in myself; Anger, lust, pride, selfishness. By the grace of God, I hope never to commit such terrible acts, but I know internally that I have no better moral standing than the people who have.\n\nWhich brings me to the second truth;\n\n<strong>Christ is a great savior.</strong> As scandalous as this may be, Jesus had so much love for us dirty, broken humans that he devoted His entire life, even to the point of dying, just to communicate this message; that no matter how dirty we are, whatever awful thoughts we''ve entertained or whatever heinous crimes we''ve committed, God wants to bring us back into a relationship with Him. A relationship where our guilt has been paid for, where we have no shame for any of our dirt or darkness, where our entire identity is summed up in the statement, "You''re my child, and I love you no matter what!"\n\nMaybe this is too spiritual for some of you. Too religious, too condemning, or too judgmental. But please hear this; this is the core reason, in fact, the only reason, why I''m able to call myself a Christian and why I am working as "a missionary" at Doulos. It''s not because I''m a good person. It''s not because I''m spiritual, or religious, or moral. The simple fact is that I''m not. I''m a man with a dark and dirty heart. The only redeeming factor of my life is Christ. His unconditional love for me, and His willingness to cover my shame and claim me no matter how dirty I am.\n\nMy life is lived in light of that. I love others because Christ loved me first. I want other people to hear of God''s unconditional love and to know that it is being offered to them as well. I''m often bad person, a bad missionary, a bad example. But Jesus? Jesus is great. And he loves me. And he loves you. No matter what. And that is what truly matters.', 'I am a great sinner and Christ is a great savior', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '192-revision', '', '', '2013-01-06 18:44:40', '2013-01-06 18:44:40', '', 192, 'http://josiahsprague.com/blog/192-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
