n''t being pushed so hard and the airflow was keeping things cool. We were cruising along, happily approaching the beach at 50mph when suddenly, BOOM! The hood of the car flew up, shattering the windshield in our faces and blocking our vision! Thankfully, no glass actually cut our faces or got in our eyes, and we were on a straight road and Eric was able to safely stop the car before we hit anything or ended up off-road in a huge ditch or down the side of a mountain.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://instagram.com/p/WYGSfuTUSk/"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-296" alt="windshield" src="http://josiahsprague.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/windshield-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nThough public infrastructure and assistance isn''t so common, Dominicans are very eager to help a stranger. Within 30 seconds, another Dominican stopped to help. He was the manager of <a href="http://www.bahia-principe.com/en/">a garage about five minutes away</a>, so he helped us get the car there, where they removed the windshield and used an air compressor to blow all of the glass fragments off of the dashboard and seats. A couple of hours later, we were back on our way to the beach.\r\n\r\nWe had left at 9:30 in the morning to go to a beach less than two hours away. By the time we got there, it was 3:30 in the afternoon. We got to swim in a <a href="http://goo.gl/maps/KJy7h">beautiful crystal clear ocean</a>, and read in our <a href="http://www.socohammocks.com/">SoCo Hammocks</a> for a few hours. We had a nice Dominican-style dinner, and then drove three hours slowly back to Jarabacoa without a windshield, and nervously watching the temperature gauge to make sure that the radiator wouldn''t overheat and explode.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://instagram.com/p/WZe3GgzUS8/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-297" alt="Dominican Food" src="http://josiahsprague.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/dominican-food-presidente-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nNeither of us has any idea why we''ve experienced such a string of crazy events. But we both agree that living in the Dominican Republic is teaching us to go with the flow and realize that not everything is always under our control, but that''s ok. We''re learning to be more patient and to accept things for how the are. And to be thankful for what we have, because it really is a lot, even when we hit a rough patch or lose something valuable.', 'Car Trouble, Round Two', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '292-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-03-25 17:13:49', '2013-03-25 17:13:49', '', 292, 'http://josiahsprague.com/292-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(317, 1, '2013-02-05 14:44:26', '2013-02-05 14:44:26', 'Yesterday several of the Christian ministries around Jarabacoa got together to tour each other''s sites. We visited the <a href="http://sites.younglife.org/camps/PicoEscondido/default.aspx">Pico Escondido Young Life Camp</a>, <a href="http://www.crosswindsyouth.org/index.cfm/facilities/caribbean-mountain-academy/">Caribbean Mountain Academy</a>, <a href="http://www.sidominicanrepublic.com/dr/">Students International</a>, <a href="http://www.kidsalive.org/around-the-world/latin-america/dominican-republic/">Kids Alive</a> and <a href="http://doulosdiscovery.org">Doulos</a>. It was encouraging to see the number of people that are here, each working in separate areas, with separate focus, but all working with the same vision.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-276" alt="Sharing about Ministries in Jarabacoa" src="http://josiahsprague.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/jarabacoa-ministries-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" />\r\n\r\nToward the end of the day, a German friend of mine, who works on <a href="http://www.spiritmountaincoffee.com/">a coffee farm near Jarabacoa</a> said, in his basic English, "We are all here working for Jesus. The devil tries to keep us apart and he doesn''t like when we work together. But Jesus is our boss, and we all work for him, so let''s keep working together for Jesus."\r\n\r\n<a href="http://bible.us/8/jhn.13.34-35.amp">It is said</a> that the world will know that we are Christians by the way we love one another. Sometimes when I come face to face with conflict between missionaries I seriously question what that means. A group made up of conservatives and liberals, protestants and catholics, charismatics and stoics, lawless and legalistic seems so unlikely to have unity of heart and spirit. But yesterday I got a glimpse of it;\r\n\r\nOur love for one another is seen in the fact that we all came from different places, to do different things, without knowing each other beforehand and having very different ideas and theologies, but we''ve got a simple and powerful unity based on one thing; the love that Jesus had for us that motivates us and drives us in everything that we do.\r\n\r\nIt''s cool to be a part of the global community that even when we disagree or fight or have totally different ideas, we''re all united together in the application of the self-sacrificing love that Christ has shown to us.', 'An Unlikely Unity', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '275-revision-3', '', '', '2013-02-05 14:44:26', '2013-02-05 14:44:26', '', 275, 'http://josiahsprague.com/275-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(319, 1, '2013-01-23 18:16:04', '2013-01-23 18:16:04', 'Lately I''ve had time to dig into a lot of books on my Kindle. I really enjoy the time I spend exploring the ideas of great authors. This week I finished reading a book called "<a href="http://amzn.to/10ISPyn">What''s Wrong with the World</a>" which got me thinking a lot about what I can do to benefit the small slice of the world that I have the opportunity to interact with.\r\n\r\nA chapter in the book that really grabbed my attention was about <a title="Innovative approach to education that I dig. Unrelated to the post at hand." href="http://doulosdiscovery.org/why-expeditionary-learning/">what it means to educate</a> others, and how clearly establishing our own personal beliefs is essential to educating others with a clear conscience. Teaching others, especially children, is not something to be taken lightly. The book says "Education is violent... it is what all human action is; it is an interference with life and growth." In light of the influence I have on others, my usual habit of carelessly sharing with others what "I think" or what "I feel" is irresponsible.\r\n\r\nThis got me thinking (like a huge nerd) about clarifying my own beliefs about the world, and establishing my own creed (or statement of what I believe to be true), before I dare to influence others. As I''ve begun evaluating and clarifying my beliefs, I was asking myself; "What do I accept as the core of reality?"\r\n\r\nThere are a lot of reasons behind my conclusion that I won''t take the time to go into here, but as I was thinking about the question, I came across a line in another book, "<a href="http://amzn.to/148H7Mp">Common Prayer: A Liturgy for Ordinary Radicals</a>" that describes one key aspect of the answer;\r\n<blockquote>God has "lived in community" from eternity as Father, Son and Holy Spirit. God as Trinity is the core reality of the universe, and that means that <em>the core of reality is community</em>.</blockquote>\r\n<strong>The core of reality <a href="http://emmausroadaustralia.blogspot.com/2007/11/relational-god.html">has to do with relationships</a>. It''s <a href="http://www.christinyou.net/pages/understandgod.html">not abstract, distant, or meaningless</a>. It is <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/2co.4.17.niv">more significant than any event in history, and any human suffering</a>. It''s something that <a href="http://booksbycslewis.blogspot.com/2009/11/echoes-of-eden.html">we have all heard echoes</a> of, but something <a href="http://marshill.com/2012/04/21/i-dont-deserve-anything-but-jesus-has-given-me-everything">none of us can reach or deserve</a>. <a href="http://ruthwilson.theworldrace.org/?filename=freaking-hard">To participate in it is painful</a>, but <a href="http://cootsona.blogspot.com/2012/01/c-s-lewis-on-hell-of-not-loving.html">to be cut off from it is hell</a>. It is something <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/rom.8.22-23.niv">to which we long to be restored</a>, and <a href="http://www.wilderness-cry.net/bible_study/malone/everyone_saved.html">which longs to be restored to us</a>. It is something that <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/97/mat.22.9.msg">all are welcome to participate</a> in but <a href="http://www.everystudent.com/forum/miracles2.html">none are forced</a>. It is <a href="http://sojo.net/blogs/2012/11/05/god-still-not-republican-or-democrat">not something that anyone owns or controls</a>. <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/1jn.4.8.niv">It is love</a>, <a href="https://www.bible.com/bible/180/gal.4.7.tniv">it is a family</a>, <a href="http://bible.us/111/rom.12.4-5.niv">it is a body</a>.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe implications of that are huge.\r\n\r\n<em>Have you caught a glimpse of that reality? Have you tested it to see whether it can serve as the foundation for all that you know? Have you considered the invitation to enter into a restored relationship with reality?</em>', 'The Core of Reality is Community', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '263-revision-5', '', '', '2013-01-23 18:16:04', '2013-01-23 18:16:04', '', 263, 'http://josiahsprague.com/263-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(321, 1, '2013-01-07 00:57:12', '2013-01-07 00:57:12', 'Often, at <a href="http://doulosdiscovery.org">Doulos</a>, I get praise from others. People see me as a "good person", "a missionary", "a volunteer". At times, that sort of identity is easy to embrace. After all, who doesn''t want to be seen as a good person? I enjoy believing that I''ve earned it, that I''m a good guy, that I do good work, and that I''m faithful. But the problem with that, is that <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/rom.3.10.niv"><em>it''s a lie</em></a>. When I''m honest with myself about the things that I''m tempted by, and the things that I''m capable of, I see how dark my heart really is.  I love this quote;\r\n<blockquote>My memory is nearly gone;\r\nbut I remember two things;\r\nThat I am a great sinner, and\r\nthat Christ is a great Saviour.\r\n<cite><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Newton">John Newton (1725-1807)</a></cite></blockquote>\r\nThese are my two greatest convictions in life. I hope that when I am old, and my memory begins to fade, or when I die and the memory of me begins to fade in my friends and family, that these truths remain.\r\n\r\n<strong>I am a great sinner.</strong> Over the holiday break I was faced with temptations that are uglier than I wish to describe publicly. Every time I hear stories of a <a href="http://www.grandrapidscrosswaycommunitychurch.com/sandy-hook-sadness/">mass murder</a>, a <a href="http://www.relevantmagazine.com/slices/sad-horrible-story-steubenville-ohios-rape-crew">terrible rape</a>, <a href="http://www.christianpost.com/news/jerry-sandusky-is-he-a-christian-61960/">child abuse</a>, <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/chris-rodda/hey-general-petraeus-hows_b_2122699.html">marital infidelity</a>, and other tragic events that are so obviously the action of a sick or broken person, I am aware that the seeds for such terrible actions exist in myself; <a href="http://bible.us/111/mat.5.21-22.niv">anger</a>, <a href="http://bible.us/111/mat.5.27-28.niv">lust</a>, <a href="http://bible.us/111/pro.16.18.niv">pride</a>, <a href="http://bible.us/111/jas.3.16.niv">selfishness</a>. By the grace of God, I hope never to commit such terrible acts, but I know internally that I have no better moral standing than the people who have.\r\n\r\nWhich brings me to the second truth;\r\n\r\n<strong>Christ is a great savior.</strong> As scandalous as this may be, Jesus had so much love for us dirty, broken humans that he devoted His entire life, <a href="http://bible.us/111/php.2.8.niv">even to the point of dying</a>, just to communicate this message; <em>that no matter how dirty we are, whatever awful thoughts we''ve entertained or whatever heinous crimes we''ve committed, God wants to bring us back into a relationship with Him.</em> A relationship where our guilt has been paid for, where we have no shame for any of our dirt or darkness, where He cleans us up and where our entire identity is summed up in the statement, "<a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/gal.4.7.niv">You''re my child, and I love you no matter what!</a>"\r\n\r\nMaybe this is too spiritual for some of you. Too religious, too condemning, or too judgmental. For others, maybe it is too worldly  too sinful, or too immoral. <strong>But please hear this;</strong> <em>this is the core reason, in fact, the only reason, why I''m able to call myself a Christian and why I am working as "a missionary" at Doulos.</em> It''s not because I''m a good person. It''s not because I''m spiritual, or religious, or moral. <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/1ti.1.15.niv">The simple fact is that I''m not</a>. I''m a man with a dark and dirty heart. The <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/php.3.8.niv">only redeeming factor</a> of my life is Christ. His unconditional love for me, and His willingness to cover my shame and claim me no matter how dirty I am.\r\n\r\nMy life is lived in light of that. I love others <a href="https://www.youversion.com/bible/111/1jn.4.19.niv">because Christ loved me first</a>. I want other people to hear of God''s unconditional love and to know that it is being offered to them as well. I''m often bad person, <a href="http://www.theveryworstmissionary.com/">a bad missionary</a>, a bad example. But Jesus? Jesus is great. And he loves me. And he loves you. No matter what. And that is what truly matters.', 'I''m Not A Good Person', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '192-revision-6', '', '', '2013-01-07 00:57:12', '2013-01-07 00:57:12', '', 192, 'http://josiahsprague.com/192-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(322, 1, '2012-10-23 23:48:02', '2012-10-23 23:48:02', 'I don''t think moving out of the country is so hard. When I started telling people that I was moving to the Dominican Republic, tons of people sounded impressed. I listened, proudly soaking in the praise, as many of my friends expressed their disbelief that it was so easy for me to just pick up my whole life and move out of the country. "Sure, it will be difficult", I would tell them, "but I''m not afraid". And I''m tenacious. I press on when things are difficult and frustrating. I don''t give up easily, I''m not a wuss. But I have to admit something...\r\n\r\nI can''t do this.\r\n\r\nI have reached the end of my self-sufficiency. I have given all of myself, and it is not enough. I''m not good enough. I''m not patient enough. I''m not wise enough. I''m not righteous enough. I am lonely. I am frustrated. I am empty.\r\n\r\nThe last couple of weeks, these words have constantly been on my mind;\r\n<blockquote>For the eyes of the Lord move to and fro throughout the earth that He may strongly support those whose heart is completely His.</blockquote>\r\nI''ve been wrestling with that truth, and realizing that my heart is in so many other places other than with the Lord. I have allowed the things of this world to become more exalted in my heart than God.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I want a social life. I don''t want to stay at home alone and read. I want to go out. I want to have a beer with friends, when I want and where I want. I don''t want to be left out.</li>\r\n	<li>I want a wife and a family. I don''t want to watch all of my friends get married and have babies and feel like I am missing out on the celebration. I want to love sacrificially in a lasting and worthwhile relationship.</li>\r\n	<li>I want success. I don''t want to keep working at the bottom. I want to start a web development business, I want to make money and have financial freedom and create things that make a difference in the world.</li>\r\n	<li>I want respect. I don''t others to look down on me. I want to be seen as wise and I want people to listen to what I say. I don''t want to have to defend my opinion. I want my reputation to defend it for me.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMy heart is desperate for all of these things, and they are all being stripped away from me. It is a painful process, one that I am fighting tooth and nail to resist. But I am done. I can''t do it anymore. It is time for me to give up on my self-sufficiency, and give up on my idols and confess to God that He is the only thing I can count on, and He is the only thing I need.', 'I Can''t Do This', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '175-revision-4', '', '', '2012-10-23 23:48:02', '2012-10-23 23:48:02', '', 175, 'http://josiahsprague.com/175-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(374, 1, '2013-04-25 11:18:01', '2013-04-25 11:18:01', '<p>Facebook is easy, real friendship is not. Facebook is a lie. That''s why I quit.</p>\n\n<p>Reasons To Quit Facebook\n* Real Friendships Take Real Effort\n* Facebook Is Compulsive</p>\n\n<p>My Objections to Quitting Facebook</p>\n\n<p>Other Objections to Quitting Facebook</p>\n\n<p>Do You Think Facebook Is Evil? What about Mark Zuckerberg?</p>\n\n<p>I wouldn''t call Mark Zuckerberg evil. He may be mistaken about a few things, just as I may be mistaken about a few things, but I believe he is a person created to be a reflection of God just like every other person.</p>\n\n<p>I do think Facebook is evil. That doesn''t mean I think anyone that works for Facebook is evil, or that using Facebook is evil. But any platform that''s success is based on people buying into lies is evil. </p>\n', 'Facebook is too easy, I quit!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-04-25 11:18:01', '2013-04-25 11:18:01', '', 372, 'http://josiahsprague.com/372-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
