(395, 1, '2013-04-30 19:53:47', '2013-04-30 19:53:47', '<p>Facebook is easy, real friendship is not. Facebook is a lie. That''s why I quit.</p>\n\n<h2>Reasons To Quit Facebook</h2>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/">Real Friendships Take Real Effort</a>\nNothing worth anything is cheap.</li>\n<li>Facebook Is Compulsive\nI don''t think I suffer from Facebook addiction. I''m not a mental health professional, but I''m not sure that it''s possible to be addicted to Facebook. What I do know is that Facebook creates compulsive behavior. I don''t want to be compelled by a company.</li>\n<li>Facebook Isn''t Important\n"those who use the things of the world, as if not engrossed in them. For this world in its present form is passing away" 1 cor 7:31</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>My Objections to Quitting Facebook</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>I chat with a lot of people on Facebook\nGet in touch with the people I''ve regularly chatted with and tell them I''ve leaving Facebook. Other options for chat are; Google, SMS, Twitter.</li>\n<li>I get a lot of blog traffic through Facebook\nAsk people who read my blog to subscribe via email. Campaign about this for two weeks on Facebook, Blog and through email.</li>\n<li>I log into a lot of other websites with my Facebook account\nTurn of Facebook platform and use Twitter or create an account instead.</li>\n<li>I use Facebook for work\nCreate a Facebook account with a fake name and no friends.</li>\n<li>I can contact anyone through Facebook\nExport contacts and maintain an actual address book: Google Contacts</li>\n<li>Facebook is how other people share photos with me\nAsk them to share photos in person, or through?...</li>\n<li>You never know when you''ll need your Facebook network. Social support - Byker''s story</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Other Objections to Quitting Facebook</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>I get my news from Facebook</li>\n<li>That is how person X communicates. Communicating on their level.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Do You Think Facebook Is Evil? What about Mark Zuckerberg?</h2>\n\n<p>I wouldn''t call Mark Zuckerberg evil. He may be mistaken about a few things, just as I may be mistaken about a few things, but I believe he is a person created to be a reflection of God just like every other person.</p>\n\n<p>I do think Facebook is evil. That doesn''t mean I think anyone that works for Facebook is evil, or that using Facebook is evil. But any platform that''s success is based on people buying into lies is evil. </p>\n\n<h2>How Do I Quit Facebook?</h2>\n\n<p>You can permanently delete your Facebook account here. That requires you to wait for two whole weeks and be careful to to use any website that you signed up for with Facebook. That''s plenty of time to second guess your decision. I wanted to have a little bit more control over my Facebook use and my decision to quit, so this is how I quit Facebook.</p>\n', 'Facebook is too easy, I quit!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-04-30 19:53:47', '2013-04-30 19:53:47', '', 372, 'http://josiahsprague.com/372-revision-16/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(397, 1, '2013-05-01 11:37:10', '2013-05-01 11:37:10', '<p>My list of reasons to quit Facebook has been slowly growing, but Facebook''s useful features have kept me hanging on until now. A few weeks ago I watched <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=voWvqBsyYbE">an advertisement for Facebook Home</a> that put the final nail in the coffin.</p>\n\n<p>The video portrays a girl, about my age, apparently bored at a family gathering. She does what has become an infamous habit in our world; she pulls out her phone for something more entertaining.</p>\n\n<p>The fact that she is more interested in her phone than in the people around her isn''t shocking. We see this happen every day. I even see it here in the Dominican Republic. The thing that is shocking is the extent to which Facebook is celebrating and encouraging the habit. It''s offensive.</p>\n\n<p>The girl in the video is the antithesis of who I want to be, but she is exactly wants us to be, and has wanted us to be from the beginning: discontent. Facebook started as a popularity contest web page on the Harvard campus. It fed off of discontent people who were comparing themselves to others. As it has grown, it has always promised to help us connect to our friends. But it''s true driving force has never been hidden too far beneath the surface: capitalizing on our feeling of disconnectedness.</p>\n\n<p>The irony is that Facebook is making us more disconnected. Facebook is easy, real friendship is not. Facebook is a lie. That''s why I quit.</p>\n\n<h2>Reasons To Quit Facebook</h2>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/">Real Friendships Take Real Effort</a>\nNothing worth anything is cheap.</li>\n<li>Facebook Is Compulsive\nI don''t think I suffer from Facebook addiction. I''m not a mental health professional, but I''m not sure that it''s possible to be addicted to Facebook. What I do know is that Facebook creates compulsive behavior. I don''t want to be compelled by a company.</li>\n<li>Facebook Isn''t Importa