(507, 1, '2013-11-22 13:46:13', '2013-11-22 13:46:13', 'A few weeks ago, many of us experienced hurricane Sandy. Here in Jarabacoa, it was hardly more than a rainy day. Many of my friends in Ohio were out of power for a few days, and friends on the east coast witnessed some flooding first hand. I don''t personally know anyone who was hit very hard by the storm, but I know very few people who weren''t on alert about it. Storms bring a lot of chaos and danger, and it is only normal to be on alert when a storm is coming in.\r\n\r\nI was reading a story yesterday about a group of fishermen who were caught in a storm. They had been attending a public speaking event near <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_of_Galilee">Lake Tiberias</a>, and afterward they set sail in a small group of boats with the man who had been speaking. Soon after they set out, they found themselves caught in an intense storm and their tiny boat began filling with water. The fishermen were all on alert, but the speaker of the event was <em>asleep in the midst of the chaotic storm</em>.\r\n\r\nStorms have woken many of us while we''re safe and secure in our houses. It seems hard to believe that this man would have been able to sleep through an intense storm in a little boat that was filling with water. It kind of makes you wonder what this guy''s deal was. Was he crazy, or what? I bet the fishermen who were with him in the boat were wondering the same thing. They were probably even a bit annoyed that he was sleeping instead of grabbing a pail or a rope and helping them to keep the boat from sinking.\r\n\r\nWhat happened next in the story is even harder to believe, but it explains exactly why this guy was able to sleep through the storm. The fishermen yelled at him to wake him up, "Dude, wake up! Don''t you care that this boat is sinking?!". The speaker woke up, and without saying a word to the fishermen, looked up at the sky and said, "Enough! Be calm!" and<em> the waves instantly stopped tossing, and the skies cleared up</em>. Then, he turned to the fishermen and said, "Why are you afraid? Don''t you know who controls the storms?".\r\n\r\nI''d imagine if any of us had experienced that, we would have been pretty freaked out. The fishermen, who were used to handling a boat on a stormy sea, were probably more freaked out by this guy than they were by the storm. I mean, <em>who IS this guy</em>? All he has to do is say a word and he can make a raging storm stop instantly. The real thing to fear is not the storms, but the guy who can control them.\r\n\r\nIf you haven''t caught on by now, there are <a title="Mark 4:35-41" href="http://bible.us/111/mrk.4.35-41.niv">three</a> <a title="Matthew 8:23-27" href="http://bible.us/111/mat.8.23-27.niv">historical</a> <a title="Luke 8:22-25" href="http://bible.us/111/luk.8.22-25.niv">accounts</a> of this story, and the people in the boat were Jesus and his disciples. This experience taught the disciples a clear lesson about who God is, and we can learn from it as well. We often have our own storms. The chaos and struggles of life threaten to drown us if we don''t stay on alert and work hard to keep things from going under. Sometimes the last thing we are able to do is to rest in the midst of the chaos of life.\r\n\r\nMy own life has felt very vulnerable to being overwhelmed by the wind and waves of life in the last several months. I''ve experienced the chaos of wondering where my paycheck will come from, driving on some crazy roads with some crazy Dominican drivers, not understanding the language of my neighbors and not knowing who I can trust or who is out to take advantage of a naive gringo. It can be hard to rest when you''re constantly fighting to stay afloat.\r\n\r\nBut this story can teach us how to rest in the midst of a storm. Jesus'' question to his disciples was, "Why are you afraid? Do you still have no faith?" The key to having peace in a storm is to know the one who sets it''s boundaries and stills it''s fury, and to fear Him more than we fear the raging waters around us.\r\n\r\nI have been learning to trust God more than I fear the storms. I still have a lot to learn, but I know that I can rest knowing that God sets the limits and that all of the raging storms in my life are stilled at His command. What about you? <em>What or who do you fear? Do you trust God more than you fear the storms? Are you able to sleep through storms?</em>', 'Sleeping Through Storms', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '188-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:46:13', '2013-11-22 13:46:13', '', 188, 'http://josiahsprague.com/188-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(508, 1, '2013-11-22 13:46:17', '2013-11-22 13:46:17', 'Last week I wrote about my realization that <a title="I Can’t Do This" href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/i-cant-do-this/">I can''t do this</a>, that I''m at the end of my rope with living in a foreign culture and with living a good life. This is a very real heart-crisis for me, but I want to clarify to those of you who were concerned, I am not considering leaving Jarabacoa or Doulos. I am still convinced that this is where I am supposed to be right now.\r\n\r\nThe (mostly internal) trials that I am facing are painful, and I''d honestly like to avoid them, but they are <a title="Consider it pure joy whenever you encounter trials..." href="http://bible.us/100/jas.1.2-4.nasb">shaping me in a good way</a>, and in a way that I wouldn''t otherwise be shaped without them.\r\n\r\nWhen I read the Bible, I often notice that Jesus'' disciples, who had the privilege of being with Him in person, just didn''t get it. They didn''t understand who Jesus was, or what He was up to. I can relate to that. I''ve spent my entire life in close proximity to churches and religious institutions that are all centered around Jesus, and I can explain the simple truth of the Gospel in 50 different ways. But when it comes to my own salvation, it is still very much <a href="http://bible.us/100/php.2.12-13.nasb">a messy issue that I am working out daily</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_181" align="alignleft" width="300"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-181" alt="A Kitten at Doulos" src="http://josiahsprague.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/ac3fec1221d311e2b3af22000a1fb856_7-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" /> At times I feel as helpless as this Kitten that we found in the workshop at Doulos.[/caption]\r\n\r\nJust as the disciples, who were daily with Jesus in the flesh, I have no clue what Jesus is about.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sometimes I think Jesus is about living a well-rounded life.</strong>\r\n\r\nSo often in Christian communities we hold up people who have their life together; who are healthy, happy, wealthy and wise. At times, I feel envious when I am not exalted by others as being noble or strong or wise.\r\n\r\n<em>But Jesus is not about me having my life together. <a href="http://bible.us/100/1co.1.26-31.nasb">He is about using my weak, foolish, and sometimes despised self for His glory</a>.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sometimes I think Jesus is about having rewarding friendships.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe second greatest commandment, Jesus said, was to love your neighbor as yourself. I can''t envision a way to live out that truth without being a friend to my neighbor.  As an extrovert, I am very comfortable with the idea of being friends with everyone. I will almost never pass up an opportunity to be with friends.\r\n\r\n<em>But Jesus is not about me having an entertaining social life. <a href="http://bible.us/100/mat.5.46.nasb">He is about loving others even when they don''t love back</a>, and <a href="http://bible.us/100/mrk.1.35.nasb">He frequently separated Himself from His closest friends to spend time alone with God</a>.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sometimes I think Jesus is about being materially successful.</strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_182" align="alignleft" width="300"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-182" alt="Wildflower in Jarabacoa" src="http://josiahsprague.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/0cede6c2205311e29f3f22000a1f978e_7-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" /> Even when we are helpless, God takes care of us. (Luke 12:27-28)[/caption]\r\n\r\nCertainly working hard is a good thing, and a hard worker is worthy of his wages. I feel that if I work hard, I am entitled to a reward. I look forward to having a car (that works), and a house (with a big yard), and a lot of money to spend.\r\n\r\n<em> But Jesus isn''t about making bank. <a href="http://bible.us/100/mat.6.19-21.nasb">He said that where our money goes has a lot to do with where our heart is, and that we shouldn''t place too much value in physical stuff that won''t last</a>.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sometimes I think Jesus is about communicating well.</strong>\r\n\r\nA lot of the role models that I have are good communicators. C.S. Lewis was an amazing writer. Brian Kunkler is a great speaker. Jesus himself was pretty good at communication. I studied Communication in college and I often take pride in my ability to communicate well.\r\n\r\n<em>But Jesus isn''t about choosing people based on their ability to communicate cleverly. <a href="http://bible.us/100/exo.4.10.nasb">Moses could barely handle public speaking</a>, and <a href="http://bible.us/100/1co.2.1-4.nasb">Paul said that persuasive words don''t matter</a>.</em>\r\n\r\nLife in Jarabacoa is wrecking my ideas about what Jesus is about. My life is not as well rounded as I think it should be. But I am learning that God can use me anyway. My social life is not as strong as it was in the States, but I am learning that my relationship with God matters more than being accepted by others. I am not earning as much money as I want to be earning, but I am learning that the things I often value are an illusion. Sometimes I feel that the only things that are going smoothly are my work on the Doulos website, and my efforts to learn Spanish, but I am learning that those don''t earn me any more credit with God.\r\n\r\nI am learning that, just like His disciples, I have no clue what Jesus is about. But He is teaching me and changing me on a daily basis. I am joyful in the struggles I am facing, knowing that they are drawing my closer to Jesus and turning me into <a href="http://bible.us/100/jas.1.4.nasb">a person who has everything</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'I Have No Clue What Jesus Is About', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '180-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:46:17', '2013-11-22 13:46:17', '', 180, 'http://josiahsprague.com/180-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(509, 1, '2013-11-22 13:46:22', '2013-11-22 13:46:22', 'A few weeks ago, I moved into a new house in Jarabacoa with two other roommates. My first couple of weeks here, I lived with a host family who were very generous and welcoming as I began my transition to living in Dominican culture. Living in this new house is allowing me to transition more into life and experiences here.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_164" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/4bd7337c16ce11e291a022000a1e8839_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-164" title="My House" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/4bd7337c16ce11e291a022000a1e8839_7-300x300.jpg" alt="My House" width="300" height="300" /></a> I live in the house on the left with a red roof.[/caption]\r\n\r\nOne of the things that I am excited about living in my own apartment is the ability to host friends. It is common in Dominican culture to gather at friends'' houses, rather than going out together. Without having my own place where I could host friends, I felt that it was difficult to initiate or reciprocate friendships with Dominicans, but now, thankfully, I have that ability.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_165" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/ae6bd4d80a6811e29f481231380fd1fd_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-165" title="Hanging out on the Porch" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/ae6bd4d80a6811e29f481231380fd1fd_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Hanging out on the Porch" width="300" height="300" /></a> Singing and playing guitar on my porch with Dominican and German friends.[/caption]\r\n\r\nHaving friends over to my house has given me more opportunities to learn Spanish, which is something I absolutely enjoy doing, and allowed me to experience Latin America''s famous dancing talent (and Gringos'' comparative lack of dancing talent) first hand. If you''re wondering why I''m not in this picture, you''ve obviously never seen me try to dance.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_166" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/6b5099c40aa711e299b11231381b6f02_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-166" title="Friends Dancing" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/6b5099c40aa711e299b11231381b6f02_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Friends Dancing" width="300" height="300" /></a> My friends Steph and Natali dancing in my house.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI''ve also been able to take my experience with Dominican cuisine to the next level, now that I have my own kitchen in which to cook. I''ve learned how to cook yuca frita, salami, queso frito and tostones (all Dominican favorites) and I''ve discovered, surprisingly, that though they live in a country full of cheap avocados, most Dominicans have never heard of guacamole. Here, apparently, it''s a Gringo thing.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_169" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/a4c42bc60e7611e2b52912313820446d_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-169" title="Burnt Tostones" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/a4c42bc60e7611e2b52912313820446d_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Burnt Tostones" width="300" height="300" /></a> My first attempt at Tostones. A little too crispy.[/caption]\r\n\r\nOne of the downsides of living in a new place is that it is farther from where I work, and I haven''t been <a title="My October Financial Needs Update" href="http://eepurl.com/pBzW9">able to afford a motorcycle</a> yet. The neighbor girls offered to let me use their "carro", but it''s not exactly my style.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_167" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/1b4a04600e8f11e286fe22000a1de753_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-167" title="Neighbors" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/1b4a04600e8f11e286fe22000a1de753_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Neighbors" width="300" height="300" /></a> My neighbors showing me their homemade "carro".[/caption]\r\n\r\nI''ve been using my longboard to get to work. Though the streets are a little rough, it always provides a little bit of entertainment with the reactions I get from people on the street. This week, on my way home, a motorcycle taxi driver asked if he could try my longboard. He quickly attracted a crowd of people, and though he swore he knew what he was doing, I don''t think he ever rode a longboard before.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_168" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/23672d5414ab11e2bf8b22000a1e8b2b_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-168" title="Concho Driver on Longboard" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/23672d5414ab11e2bf8b22000a1e8b2b_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Concho Driver on Longboard" width="300" height="300" /></a> A taxi driver on my longboard.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo, the longer commute isn''t so bad. It''s also allowed me to explore more of Jarabacoa. I found that Batman apparently has a vacation home here.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_170" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/f0145726085011e29035123138140023_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-170" title="Batmans House" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/f0145726085011e29035123138140023_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Batmans House" width="300" height="300" /></a> Batman''s Vacation Home[/caption]\r\n\r\nAnd when I finally get home from work, I can relax on my porch and enjoy the view. I definitely miss the beautiful fall weather in Ohio, but this view can definitely compete.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_163" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/63671cdc13ea11e29a5322000a1d0353_7.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-163" title="Magote from Jarabacoa" src="http://josiahsprague.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/63671cdc13ea11e29a5322000a1d0353_7-300x300.jpg" alt="Magote from Jarabacoa" width="300" height="300" /></a> The view from my porch in Jarabacoa[/caption]\r\n\r\nThank you all for your continued encouragement, prayers and support. Please <a title="Sign Up for My Email Updates" href="http://eepurl.com/pWuUX">stay in touch</a>!', 'Moving into a new Neighborhood', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '161-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:46:22', '2013-11-22 13:46:22', '', 161, 'http://josiahsprague.com/161-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(510, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:01', '2013-11-22 13:47:01', 'Here''s a quick video explaining what I''m going to be doing for the next few years. Check it out, and then check out <a href="/support/">how you can join my support team</a>!\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/1ngtPLTgJ50?rel=0" frameborder="0" width="420" height="315"></iframe>', 'Where I''m Going', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '14-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:01', '2013-11-22 13:47:01', '', 14, 'http://josiahsprague.com/14-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(511, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:05', '2013-11-22 13:47:05', '<div class="row-fluid">\r\n<div class="span8">\r\n\r\nA year ago, if you would have asked me where I saw myself in five years, any place overseas was not on the list. I had been spending the past several years settling into normal, post-college adult life, and I was beginning to get comfortable. I had an enjoyable job developing websites for a laid back eCommerce web development agency, and I envisioned myself living and working in northeast Ohio for the next several years.But alas, I didn''t know everything that was in store for me. In April, a coworker mentioned to me that he was taking a team of people to <a title="Expeditionary Learning Education in the Dominican Republic" href="http://doulosdiscovery.org/">Doulos Discovery School</a> in Jarabacoa for a week-long <a title="Missions Trip in the Dominican Republic" href="http://doulosdiscovery.org/opportunities/service-learning-trips/">Service Learning Trip</a>. The idea didn''t appeal to me, since I have had bad experiences with short term service trips in the past. But he continued to invite me and I decided, at the last minute, that the trip was a better way to spend my vacation time than any of the other ideas I had in mind.\r\n\r\nLittle did I know the huge impact that such a small decision would have on my life. (Take note; little decisions do matter.) Less than three full months later, I found myself leaving my comfortable, normal life in northeast Ohio to work full time at Doulos as their Media Coordinator. It feels a little bit crazy. There are a lot of challenges, and a lot of unknowns. But when I was presented with the opportunity, I couldn''t be content with the idea of turning it down.\r\n\r\nIt is as if I had been anticipating this opportunity my whole life, not knowing what it was until it was presented to me. The opportunity to communicate a story that I believe in, using tools with which I am trained and experienced, resonates with my soul. It is a story that I want to tell and a story in which I want to play a part.\r\n\r\nMy role at Doulos is to tell <a title="Founding Story of Doulos Discovery School" href="http://doulosdiscovery.org/about/founding-story/">the story of the school</a>—ultimately the story of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_news_(Christianity)">the Gospel</a>—using web and video media. I will be working to help Doulos create a bilingual, responsive website, which will help Doulos communicate with students, parents, community members and supporters. I will be creating videos to promote Doulos on the web and on local cable television, and I will help students and teachers communicate their stories to their sponsors.\r\n\r\nI also hope to immerse myself in Dominican culture, explore the country along with students on their <a title="Official Website of Expeditionary Learning Schools" href="http://elschools.org/">Expeditionary Learning</a> adventures and stay open to the unknown and unexpected. I expect life here to be full of ups and downs and adventures. I am all in and eager to see what God does with my life here.\r\n\r\nI welcome you to join me on this journey, please take a minute to <a href="http://eepurl.com/pbwzz">subscribe to my newsletter</a> and please email me at <a href="mailto:josiah.sprague@gmail.com">josiah.sprague@gmail.com</a> if you have any questions about how you can be a part. I am grateful for all of your thoughts, prayers and support!\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>', 'What Am I Doing in Jarabacoa?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '346-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:05', '2013-11-22 13:47:05', '', 346, 'http://josiahsprague.com/346-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(512, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:07', '2013-11-22 13:47:07', 'I was walking home from campus yesterday, and as I was passing McDonalds a man sitting at the bus stop asked me if I could give him a cigarette. I told him I didn''t have a cigarette, and that all I had was a ZipCard with a meal plan. He asked if I could get him a sandwich, so I did.\n\nAs I was waiting in line for the sandwich, I was thinking that I''m really not giving this guy much. I was thinking about what he really needs (probably); support, a job, friends, family... none of which I have the resources to give him. But as an adopted child of God through Jesus, I have access to God as a father and can ask Him for anything I need and He will provide. So I decided that I could give this man the blessing of prayer; coming before God with Him to ask God to provide for his real needs.\n\nAs I gave him his sandwich, he asked me again if I could give him a cigarette. I told him that I didn''t have one, but asked if I could give him what I do have; prayer. I had expected that he would say yes, sort of as an obligation for me buying him food, but instead his face lit up and he said, "I need that!", another man sitting on the bench said, "Hey! Can I get some of that too?" So I prayed for both of them, for all three of us- because I believe that God is faithful as a father to provide for the needs of His children.\n\nAs I left, both men were encouraged and saying, "Man, I need more of that in my life!" Isn''t that a need that we all have in common; the provision of our heavenly father who provides for all of our needs? All we have to do is ask Him.\n\n<a href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Luk&amp;c=11&amp;v=13&amp;t=NASB#13" target="_blank">Luke 11.13</a>, <a href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Luk&amp;c=18&amp;v=1&amp;t=NASB#top" target="_blank">Luke 18.1-9</a>, <a href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Mat&amp;c=7&amp;v=11&amp;t=NASB#11" target="_blank">Matthew 7.11</a>', 'What Can I Give?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '127-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:07', '2013-11-22 13:47:07', '', 127, 'http://josiahsprague.com/127-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(513, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:10', '2013-11-22 13:47:10', 'I just wanted to let everyone know, if you''re looking for a new <a href="http://www.apple.com/macbookpro/" target="_blank">MacBook</a>, <a href="http://www.uakron.edu/aux/computersolutions/" target="_blank">Computer Solutions</a> on campus is definitely the place to go. I got a new MacBook from <a href="http://www.bestbuy.com/" target="_blank">Best Buy</a> today, open box, no extra software, no accessories and it cost me $100 more than a new MacBook at Computer Solutions that comes with <a href="http://www.apple.com/ilife/" target="_blank">iLife 09</a> and a free printer. Needless to say, I''m returning my MacBook to Best Buy and getting one at Computer Solutions.\n\nOn second thought... I wonder if Best Buy will do a retroactive price match (plus 10%) and also throw in iLife and a printer? Probably not.', 'Campus Deals on New MacBooks', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '115-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:10', '2013-11-22 13:47:10', '', 115, 'http://josiahsprague.com/115-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(514, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:12', '2013-11-22 13:47:12', 'A couple of weeks ago at <a title="Campus Focus" href="http://www.campusfocus.org" target="_blank">Campus Focus</a>, Brian Kunkler said, "Seriously guys, how big do our biceps need to be to reach into the refridgerator and open a jar of pickles?" Implying that it was wrong for guys to work for bigger biceps. This week, he asked for a <a title="What is a Mulligan?" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mulligan" target="_blank">Mulligan</a> because he believes that Christians should do whatever they do for the glory of God, even if that "whatever" is working for bigger biceps.\n\nBrian talked about <a title="Colossians 3 - Blue Letter Bible" href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Col&amp;c=3&amp;t=NIV" target="_blank">Colossians 3</a>. He sees a grid of three things that Christians should run their activities through;\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>"Put to death" things that go against the revealed moral will of God.</strong> The things listed in Colossians 3.5-8 that go against the moral will of God include; sexual immorality, impurity, lust, evil desires, greed (which is idolatry), anger, rage, malice, slander and filthy language.</li>\n	<li><strong>Whose glory are we seeking?</strong> God has given us value as human beings and it is not anything we have to work for or earn. Colossians 3.11 says that Christ takes away any human measures of value- everyone is equally valuable (student, non-student, homeless, healthy, black, white, gay, straight...). Whatever Christians do should not be to earn respect from people, but to give glory to God.</li>\n	<li><strong>"Clothe yourselves with" virtues of God''s character.</strong> The virtues listed in Colossians 3.12 include; compassion, kindness, humility, gentleness, patience, forgiveness (as Christ forgave you), and love, which binds all of these virtues together in unity.</li>\n</ol>\nTo sum up these three parts of the grid, Brian points to Colossians 3.17; "Whatever you do in word or deed, do all in the name of Jesus, giving thanks through Him to God the Father."\n\nThe second part of the grid hit me really hard. Everything that I have been doing this semester has been motivated by a desire to earn people''s respect (my professors, my residents, my boss, my girlfriend, my small group, my roommates, etc). Something that Brian noticed, that I completely agree with, is that doing something to try to earn someone''s respect has a tendency to destroy the pleasure of that activity.\n\nI''ve come to the realization that there are some things that God hasn''t blessed me with (such as big biceps). If I am seeking to bless myself with these things I am probably not seeking God''s glory (so that people will worship God when they see how wonderfully He has made me) but I am seeking my own glory (so that people will respect me when they see the man that I have made myself to be).\n\n(Check out <a title="Campus Focus Podcast" href="http://itunes.apple.com/WebObjects/MZStore.woa/wa/viewPodcast?id=326679776" target="_blank">the weekly podcast of Campus Focus </a>to hear Brian''s message from this week as well as previous weeks.)', 'Mulligan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '104-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:12', '2013-11-22 13:47:12', '', 104, 'http://josiahsprague.com/104-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(515, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:15', '2013-11-22 13:47:15', 'At the beginning of the semester, I wrote a proposal for the <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu" target="_blank">University of Akron</a> to install bike racks near the <a title="Townhouses - Residence Life &amp; Housing" href="http://www.uakron.edu/reslife/townhouses.php" target="_blank">Townhouses</a> where I live. I thought the proposal had gone un-noticed, and partly, since my bike was stolen, I didn''t really care. But I just got news today that the bike racks should be installed in the coming weeks. It''s a little late in the season to be of much use now, but I am excited that we''ll have bike racks in the spring. Townhouse residents'' bikes will be closer to their homes, which is both convenient and more safe. My hope is that this encourages Townhouse residents to ride their bikes more. For a list of reasons that I think this is valuable, <a title="Bike Rack Proposal [DOC]" href="http://dl.getdropbox.com/u/159889/BIKE%20RACK%20PROPOSAL.doc" target="_blank">check out my original proposal</a>.', 'Bike Racks Coming to the Townhouses', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '98-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:15', '2013-11-22 13:47:15', '', 98, 'http://josiahsprague.com/98-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(516, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:18', '2013-11-22 13:47:18', 'In my earlier post about the Community Zipnic I had mentioned that, by appearances, the picnic was a success. I promised more thoughts on that, so here they are.\n\nAlmost everyone that I had hoped for was at the picnic, and then some. Almost. It seemed like most of the people at the picnic were students. And I didn''t see the men from the neighborhood whom I had invited.  My eyes were on the gate, anxiously hoping that I would see them.\n\nThat''s when I noticed that a UAPD officer was at the gate turning people away. That''s when I had to start asking myself what we were doing; We''re turning people away? From a free community picnic? Did we just turn that guy away because he looked homeless? Even if he is homeless, he still lives in the community- we ought to be ashamed if we are <a title="Isaiah 58:7 on BlueLetterBible.com" href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Isa&amp;c=58&amp;t=NIV#7" target="_blank">turning away our own flesh and blood</a>.\n\nI turned to someone and asked, "If someone is a member of the community, should they not be invited to the picnic?"\n\n"No, we didn''t invite sex offenders and criminals. We skipped the houses of sex offenders and criminals when we passed out fliers."\n\nI was frustrated that we were having this picnic to build a sense of community in the neighborhood so that future crime would be reduced and that everyone in the community was invited, except anyone with a criminal record. Oh, and anyone who looked dirty or unshaven, was being turned away too.\n\nI was wondering how many people at the picnic actually live in the neighborhood compared to people who were students just staying in the neigborhood temporarily. Associated Student Government kept track of who attended, so I got in touch with their office to get some statistics.\n\nThe statistics from the first Zipnic, which I attended weren''t very detailed- 281 people signed in. I didn''t attend the second picnic, but according to the statistics,  only 26% of the 351 people at the picnic were non-students. I can''t help but wonder if that percentage would have been higher if we hadn''t excluded those who don''t fit into our college student social class.\n\nAre these statistics a big deal? Not really... but are they indicative of a bigger problem? I think they may be... more thoughts later.', 'Community Zipnic Stats', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '87-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:18', '2013-11-22 13:47:18', '', 87, 'http://josiahsprague.com/87-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(517, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:21', '2013-11-22 13:47:21', 'I got my bike stolen at the beginning of this semester. I left it locked up by itself outside of Grant Residence Hall a week before classes started. I left it for a week, and when I came back for it, it was gone. In retrospect, I should have known better.\n\nPreventing theft is common sense, but sometimes we all need a little reminder. Hopefully it doesn''t take your bike getting stolen to remind you. I got an email from the University of Akron this weekend with a few useful tips for preventing theft. Some reminders based on their email;\n<ul type="disc">\n	<li>Don''t leave valuables where they are going to catch attention, like your car seat or the front window of your house. If potential thieves never see your valuables, they won''t be tempted.</li>\n	<li>Don''t leave valuables unsecured. Most thefts are crimes of opportunity. Thieves keep their eyes open for opportunities, but most thieves aren''t willing to do the work to make opportunities- don''t make the opportunities for them.</li>\n	<li>If you have valuables you are worried about losing, consider getting insurance coverage and/or an alarm system.</li>\n	<li>If you notice anything suspicious, let UA’s police department know. Call the department at 330-972-2911 at any hour.</li>\n</ul>\nThese are some good tips to remember. I''d like to add one more of my own that most people probably won''t like, but that I believe is the most important and timeless piece of advice;\n<ul>\n	<li>Don''t have a lot of stuff. There are better ways to invest your wealth than in material things. Consider the wisdom of <a title="Matthew 6.19 - Blue Letter Bible" href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Mat&amp;c=6&amp;v=19&amp;t=NASB#19" target="_blank">Matthew 6.19</a>;  "Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth... where thieves break in and steal..." And one of my favorite quotes from <a title="The Shepherd of Hermas - Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Shepherd_of_Hermas" target="_blank">The Shepherd of Hermas</a> in 140AD; "Instead of fields, buy for yourselves people in distress in accordance with your means." And more from <a title="Matthew 6.19 - Blue Letter Bible" href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Mat&amp;c=6&amp;v=19&amp;t=NASB#19" target="_blank">Matthew 6</a>; "where your treasure is, there your heart will be also."</li>\n</ul>', 'Where your treasure is...', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '91-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:21', '2013-11-22 13:47:21', '', 91, 'http://josiahsprague.com/91-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(518, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:24', '2013-11-22 13:47:24', 'I''ve been a part of planning a lot of picnics, parties, and banquets on campus lately. All of that leaves me thinking about the words of Jesus recorded by <a title="Luke the Evangelist - Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luke_the_Evangelist" target="_blank">Luke</a> <a title="Luke 14.12-14" href="http://www.blueletterbible.org/Bible.cfm?b=Luk&amp;c=14&amp;v=12&amp;t=NASB#12" target="_blank">in the Bible</a>;\n<blockquote>"When you give a luncheon or a dinner, do not invite your friends or your brothers or your relatives or rich neighbors, otherwise they may also invite you in return and that will be your repayment. But when you give a reception, invite the poor, the crippled, the lame, the blind, and you will be blessed,"</blockquote>\nMore thoughts on this later...', 'Picnics, Parties and Banquets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '77-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:24', '2013-11-22 13:47:24', '', 77, 'http://josiahsprague.com/77-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(519, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:27', '2013-11-22 13:47:27', 'There is often an awkward dynamic on the edge of urban college campuses where affluence meets poverty. <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a> is far from being an exception. It is a daily ritual on the edges of Akron''s campus; that awkward moment as a busy student passes a panhandler at a street corner or bus stop.\n\nSome hold signs, others tell stories. Some are visibly drunk or high, others are dirty. But the request is predictable; "My car ran out of gas around the corner. Can you help me out? I need a couple of bucks for a gas can...", "I haven''t eaten in two days and I''m hungry, do you have a ten so I can go get a pizza?", "My girl just left me with two kids and I''m just trying to get forty bucks to pay my electric bill."\n\nIt''s sad to see men and women in such distress. It evokes feelings of sympathy and a desire to help someone out. Yet helping these people often ends with the nagging thought that maybe giving money away to a stranger isn''t helping all that much. What if your sympathy is being taken advantage of? What if you''re actually feeding a person''s addiction and not the person? It''s hard not to wonder about the stranger''s motives.\n\nAccording to a <a title="Panhandling Brochurch [PDF]" href="http://www.downtownakron.com/_files/docs/panhandling-brochure.pdf">brochure</a> available from <a title="The Downtown Akron Partnership" href="http://downtownakron.com/" target="_blank">The Downtown Akron Partnership</a> most panhandlers are not homeless. In many cases, giving money to panhandlers  supports drug and alcohol addiction. Sometimes the best response is to just politely say no. Duane Crabbs, a street pastor of <a title="South Street Ministries Blog" href="http://southstreetministries.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">South Street Ministries</a> in Akron, says that when a person is struggling with addiction, almost anything you try to do for them is enabling their addiction.\n\nSympathy towards those in need is an appropriate response, but students should be wise about their giving. A number of organizations exist in and around Akron to help those in need. Students interested in giving can give to a local organization and when encountering a person in need, students can help by directing them to the appropriate organization. Students can refer to the <a title="Akron Street Card [PDF]" href="http://www.cvmsummit.net/Street%20Card%202009.pdf" target="_blank">Akron Street Card</a> for  a list of resources for those on the streets in Akron. The street card includes information about hundreds of organizations that can help with things from emergencies, to paying utilities, to getting fed and finding work.\n\nBut according to the <a title="The Haven of Rest" href="http://www.havenofrest.org" target="_blank">Haven of Rest</a>, sometimes what panhandlers truly lack is not money but bonds with others;  what many people are suffering from is a "profound disconnection from other people and institutions". Ryan Wells, a nursing student at the University of Akron, decided to face this need head on and get to know one of the panhandlers on campus;\n<blockquote>I’ve had the opportunity to get to know a gentleman who has been out of work for almost a year now. He’s got a place to crash, but no steady income, no stability. And after getting to know him, a lot of my hesitations proved true. Drugs were involved, alcohol too. But I’ve gotten to know and appreciate this man’s struggle. I can’t stress the importance of simply learning their story. Where are they at physically? Emotionally? Mentally? Spiritually? How are you really going to effectively help anyone without learning why they are the way they are? And I’ve found companionship and communication have served this man so much better than a 10-spot and a Tornado Burrito from Speedway ever could.</blockquote>\nPanhandlers are people with the same basic needs as anyone else. Don''t be afraid to get to know a panhandler. Ask them about their story. You may be surprised at what you gain from getting to know them, and they gain a friend in return. A good place to start is lunch in a public place. Not to feed them, but to sit down with them and get to know them.\n\nDISCLOSURE: This was written for a class I am enrolled in at <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu/" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a>. Duane Crabbs is the pastor of a church which I regularly attend, and Ryan Wells is a personal friend.\n\nSome other interesting reads that I came across while brainstorming for this post:\n\n<a title="Christians and the ''Art'' of Panhandling" href="http://www.boundlessline.org/2009/07/christians-and-the-art-of-panhandling.html" target="_blank">Christians and the ''Art'' of Panhandling - Boundless Line</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/article1015963.ece#" target="_blank">Panhandlers Strategies - St Petersburg Times</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.seattlepi.com/local/328421_beggar21.html" target="_blank">How Do Panhandlers Spend Your Money? - Seattle P.I.</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.internetmonk.com/archive/question-should-i-give-money-to-people-on-the-street-who-ask-for-it" target="_blank">Should I Give Money To People On The Street Who Ask For It? - Internet Monk</a>\n\n<em> </em>', 'Student, Meet Panhandler', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '38-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:27', '2013-11-22 13:47:27', '', 38, 'http://josiahsprague.com/38-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(520, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:30', '2013-11-22 13:47:30', '<div>\n\n<strong>I am excited but waiting.</strong>\n\nExcited because opportunities and open doors in my life have been abundant lately. Excited that my dreams are taking shape every day. Excited to see God working. <em>But</em>, I am waiting. Waiting because it’s not time. Waiting for the fruit to ripen. Waiting to see. Sometimes waiting because it is the wise choice, other times waiting when it’s not my choice at all. Learning to wait patiently even though I am scared.\n\n<strong>I am scared but trusting.</strong>\n\nScared that the dreams and desires on my horizon will end up crashing down. Scared of my own failure. Scared of rejection or embarrassment. Scared that I’ll miss my chance. <em>But</em>, I am trusting. Trusting that God’s heart for me is good. Trusting in His loving-kindness that is everlasting. Trusting even though His ways are not mine. Trusting Him because I am weak.\n\n<strong>I am weak but supported by God.</strong>\n\nWeak because of my fear. Weak in the face of uncertainty. Weak when faced with my own immaturity. Weak under pressure. <em>But</em>, I am supported by God. Supported by His Holy Spirit empowering me. Supported in the Body of Christ which is the Church. Supported with mercy and with Grace. And because I am supported by God’s love for me, <em>I AM EXCITED!</em></div>', 'Supported By God', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '39-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:30', '2013-11-22 13:47:30', '', 39, 'http://josiahsprague.com/39-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(521, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:34', '2013-11-22 13:47:34', '“Don’t you know that ‘Left is right and right is wrong.’?”\n\nI’ve been getting that question a lot this week. I got my right ear pieced. Yes, I do know “right is wrong” and no, I am not coming out. Getting my right ear pierced is something that I’ve been thinking about doing for awhile. I finally did it. This is my explanation.\n\nOriginally, the only men who wore earrings were bond servants. In the Bible, in the Old Testament, when a person owned a slave, the slave was to serve him for six years and in the seventh year go free. But, when the seventh year came around it was not uncommon for a freed slave to voluntarily re-enter service to the master he loved. The master would take him to the doorpost and pierce his <a href="http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=850&amp;letter=S">right ear</a> with an awl and the slave would become his bond servant for life. Only a freed slave could become a bond servant and once he had entered that service, he could never be freed again, nor could he be sold into slavery to another master. (Exodus 21:2-7)\n\nIn the New Testament, early Christians called themselves bond servants of Christ. Bond service is a two way commitment. The freed slave chooses to commit his life to the service of his master and his master commits himself to the bond servant, never to release or sell him. (Galatians 1:10, Philippians 2:7, Colossians 1:7, 2 Timothy 2:24)\n\nJesus has committed Himself to us. With His own blood, He paid our debt and freed us from the slavery of sin. We are free to serve whomever we choose. I choose Jesus, the one who loves me and gave Himself for me. He has made a commitment to love me. I have made a commitment to serve only Him. So, I got my ear pierced as symbol to all that I am a servant by choice and can neither be bought or sold.', 'Left is Right and Right is Wrong', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '40-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:34', '2013-11-22 13:47:34', '', 40, 'http://josiahsprague.com/40-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(522, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:37', '2013-11-22 13:47:37', 'I have been reading “<a title="Christ Plays in 10,000 Places on Amazon.com" href="http://www.amazon.com/Christ-Plays-Ten-Thousand-Places/dp/0802862977" target="_blank">Christ Plays in Ten Thousand Places</a>” this summer along with several other people from <a title="The Chapel in Akron" href="http://www.the-chapel.org" target="_blank">The Chapel </a>and from <a title="Summer''s Best Two Weeks" href="http://www.sb2w.org" target="_blank">Summer''s Best Two Weeks</a>. The book is full of challenges. While reflecting on my reading of the book, I wrote the following journal entry;\n<blockquote>Christ is not easy to follow. He promises life to the full, but it is not an extension of more of the things I want and admire. Full life is not in any way for my glory. but just the opposite. In order for the life and glory of God to increase in my life, I must become less. I must be willing to abandon myself, my glory and my lusts and ego, and follow Christ in death. This is difficult. Without faith in Christ, the son of God, it is impossible.</blockquote>\nI have been challenged lately to realized that following Jesus is not glamorous or sucessful. That thought doesn’t sit comfortably for me. My humanity has a natural aversion to suffering. I want as much success as possible. A quick quote from the book that caught my attention;\n<blockquote>The life of Jesus is not a happy story, not a success story. What it is… is a salvation story.</blockquote>\nI am learning more and more that following God means denying self. No matter how moral or compassionate or virtuous self may be at times, we must lose our lives to find them. Another quote that caught my attention is;\n<blockquote>The glory with which Jesus was glorified and the glory for which Jesus prayed for us is quite different from the kinds of glory that we are conditioned to want and admire. This glory is not conspicuous. It is not glamorous. It is not the glory that gets featured in glossy magazines or travel posters. It is not a glory noticed by fashion editors. It is not a glory that flatters our lusts and egos.</blockquote>\nIt is our natural tendency to use God for our own glory. But God’s glory is entirely other than our own. Time after time our behavior is deserving of Jesus words, “Get behind me Satan”, when we try to make Jesus about our own agendas and our own success instead of God’s.', 'The Glory of God', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '41-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:37', '2013-11-22 13:47:37', '', 41, 'http://josiahsprague.com/41-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
