(523, 1, '2013-11-22 13:47:40', '2013-11-22 13:47:40', 'There has been a lot of talk about the issue of race in the presidential  campaigns, especially after Obama''s recent <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/18/us/politics/18text-obama.html" target="_blank">speech  on race</a> in Philadelphia <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pWe7wTVbLUU" target="_blank">(video)</a>.  Race relationships are a complicated issue today. A <a href="http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2008-04/nu-fom040108.php" target="_blank">new  study</a> from Northwestern University suggests that many people feel anxious  during interracial interactions whether race is mentioned or not. Although the  study was only conducted with 15 white college students, I feel that I can  identify with the conclusion that "standards to create a diverse yet harmonious  society may unwittingly be encouraging anxious responses toward blacks." I am a  firm believer that <a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=galatians%203:28&amp;version=31" target="_blank">all  people are equal</a>, yet living in a very diverse neighborhood I experience  anxiety in my every day life. I tend to avoid a lot of interracial interactions  for fear of "acting wrong" and being interpreted as a racist. The study points  to the fact that our communities "need to start thinking about creating  opportunities to undermine anxieties about [interracial interactions]".  According to the study, something as simple as a smile can instantly ease  anxieties. I have experienced for myself a smile or a "hello" that has  eliminated very tense situations of passing strangers on the street. After  reading this article I have decided to face my anxieties head-on with a smile or  a friendly gesture instead of avoiding the situation altogether. Like the  community around me, I have a long way to go in developing perfect relationships  with people that are different than myself, but I am making progress, and I  encourage you to join me.', 'Easing Racial Anxieties', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '75-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:47:40', '2013-11-22 13:47:40', '', 75, 'http://josiahsprague.com/75-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(524, 1, '2013-11-22 13:48:17', '2013-11-22 13:48:17', 'In light of recent events that have illustrated that our society has a broken moral compass (really not something new), <a href="http://thefreshten.tumblr.com/">The Fresh Ten Commandments</a> have been suggested as a form of general guidance that we could use as a culture.\r\n\r\nThe original ten commandments were certainly incomplete and difficult to apply (both in modern times and when they were originally written). A modern rewrite is a great exercise to get us thinking about moral standards. Moral issues are deep and complex, so a list could never cover every situation, but as a society we might be better off morally if we kept these two rules of thumb in mind;\r\n<h2>The Two Timeless Commandments;</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>You shall love God before everything else.</strong> God is completely independent of our broken world. <a href="http://bible.us/111/jhn.13.34.niv">He is the perfect model of love that we are meant to reflect with our lives.</a> He is the source from which all morality comes.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>You shall love others with the same care with which you love yourself.</strong> All people regardless of race, gender, sexual orientation, disability, age, poverty, worldview or weakness are made with inherent dignity. You shall not undermine the dignity of others by disrespecting, murdering, raping, lying, deceiving  cheating, betraying, or otherwise taking advantage of others or of the world that you share with them.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf we got these two things right as a culture, we''d be a lot better off. Take these moral standards, make them your own, and then share them with others. Maybe, person by person, we can become the people we are supposed to be by loving our neighbors.', 'Fresh Commandments', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '330-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 13:48:17', '2013-11-22 13:48:17', '', 330, 'http://josiahsprague.com/330-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(528, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:17', '2013-11-22 14:04:17', 'A friend of mine locked her keys in her car today. We spent awhile trying to get her door unlocked using a coat hanger. We finally got it, but it got me thinking of different ways to get into your car should you lock your keys inside. I looked up some different methods, and was surprised at how many ways people suggest. There are even rumors floating around the internet that you can open a locked car with a <a title="Opening a Locked Car with a Cell Phone" href="http://www.snopes.com/autos/techno/keyless.asp" target="_blank">cell phone</a> or a <a title="Opening a Locked Car with a Tennis Ball" href="http://www.autoblog.com/2007/07/12/can-you-really-open-a-locked-door-with-a-tennis-ball/" target="_blank">tennis ball</a>. Obviously some of these methods work better than others, and the best method is to <strong>keep a spare key</strong> in your wallet, behind your license plate, or at home, but here are some of the more reliable ways to open your car if you find yourself locked out;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Call a dealership</strong> and request a replacement key. Most dealers can provide a replacement key for around five dollars. Just make sure you''re not paying the "programming fee" for newer cars, you just need the key to open the door, not start your car.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Call roadside assistance</strong> such as <a href="http://www.aaa.com" target="_blank">AAA</a> or <a href="www.onstar.com" target="_blank">OnStar</a>. These companies can send out a reputable locksmith to help you and if you are a member, the service may be included in your membership.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Call the police</strong> and ask if they can help. Many police will not open locked car doors because they do not want to be held responsible for possible damage to your car, but some police may still help so it''s worth a call. If a child or a pet is trapped in the car, police will help, call 911 if it is an emergency.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Call a local locksmith</strong> if you can find a phone book, or if you live near Akron you can use Akron Locksmith''s 24/7 Emergency Service, just call (330) 375-5260.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use a coat hanger</strong> to unlock the door yourself. This is a time-tested method of opening a locked door. You risk damaging your door if you don''t <a title="How to Open a Locked Car with a Coat Hanger" href="http://www.ehow.com/how_4474240_unlock-car-coat-hanger.html" target="_blank">know what you are doing</a>, but if you are far away from any help, this may be your best option.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use a Slim Jim</strong> for older cars. If you happen to have access to a Slim Jim, this is one of the easiest ways to open a locked car door, however, it takes <a title="How to Open a Locked Car with a Slim Jim" href="http://www.ehow.com/how_4450109_break-car-slim-jim.html" target="_blank">a little know-how</a>, and some cars are Slim Jim proof.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Use a rock, brick, or sledgehammer</strong> as a last resort if the matter is urgent. The glass can always be repaired, but please, at least count to three before you <a href="http://www.videogamesblogger.com/2009/06/19/red-faction-guerrilla-promotion-smashes-car-windows.htm" target="_blank">break anything</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Locked Out', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '129-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:17', '2013-11-22 14:04:17', '', 129, 'http://josiahsprague.com/129-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(529, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:23', '2013-11-22 14:04:23', 'The University of Akron partnered with <a href="http://fatalvision.com/">Fatal Vision</a> today to provide students with a simulated experience of drunk driving. I had the opportunity to sit inside a mechanical vehicle simulator that tilted as I watched a video monitor and tried to avoid common driving obstables first without beer goggles, and then with beer goggles to compare the experience. I have never gotten to try "beer goggles" before. I have to say that the whole experience was unrealistic. The driving simulator was awful, I''ve played more realistic driving video games at home in front of my TV. And the beer goggles, well, they might as well have been foggy goggles... no double vision, just obstructed vision.\n\nJust out of curiosity, has anyone else had an experience with DUI simulators? Did it seem realistic at all? Was it fun?', 'DUI Simulation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '113-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:23', '2013-11-22 14:04:23', '', 113, 'http://josiahsprague.com/113-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(530, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:29', '2013-11-22 14:04:29', 'Thanks to everyone who came out for our third <a href="http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/2009/09/30/b-y-o-_-round-three/" target="_blank">B.Y.O._ Cookout</a> and Pumpkin Carving Contest. We had 70 people show up, and some really creative pumpkin designs. Check out <a title="Facebook Photo Album" href="http://www.facebook.com/album.php?aid=2179506" target="_blank">the pictures</a>.\n\n<img class="alignleft" title="Pumpkin Carving" src="http://photos-a.ak.fbcdn.net/hphotos-ak-snc1/hs208.snc1/7532_621369164442_39111492_35567382_4191704_n.jpg" alt="" width="451" height="604" />', 'B.Y.O._ Round Three: Pumpkins', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '109-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:29', '2013-11-22 14:04:29', '', 109, 'http://josiahsprague.com/109-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(531, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:35', '2013-11-22 14:04:35', 'I mentioned eating lunch at the Diamond Deli yesterday, but I forgot to metion that you can easily get to the Diamond Deli via the Roo Express. I''m not very skilled at deciphering the <a title="Roo Express Routes" href="http://www.uakron.edu/aux/parking/shuttle-routes.php" target="_blank">Roo Express routes </a>or schedules, but I do know that I was able to pick up the Roo Express to get back to campus after lunch. So take a ride on the Roo Express, and check out the Diamond Deli and other great places to eat downtown!', 'Roo Express Routes', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '102-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:35', '2013-11-22 14:04:35', '', 102, 'http://josiahsprague.com/102-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(532, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:38', '2013-11-22 14:04:38', 'Sometimes the lack of locations on campus that accept Zip Cards is frustrating. If you live on the south side of campus, as I do, sometimes it seems the only place to eat is McDonald''s. Not exactly most people''s first choice. But if you want a healthier, tastier, more interesting option it''s closer than you might think.\n\nI had lunch at the <a title="Diamond Deli" href="http://www.downtownakron.com/go/diamond-deli" target="_blank">Diamond Deli</a> today in downtown Akron. The Diamond Deli offers tons of creatively named sandwiches. I''ve tried two, and they were both fantastic. They also have a very warm, welcoming atmosphere and they''re just a couple of blocks away from campus. It''s just a short walk with a couple friends on a cozy afternoon and a great alternative to McDonald''s.', 'Diamond Deli', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '100-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:38', '2013-11-22 14:04:38', '', 100, 'http://josiahsprague.com/100-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(533, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:43', '2013-11-22 14:04:43', 'I talked the other day about how <a title="Community Zipnic Stats" href="http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/2009/10/07/community-zipnic-stats/" target="_blank">I felt that we had excluded people from our Community Zipnic</a>. I heard it justified as "safety", but I''m calling it how I see it. This was a picnic in the middle of the day, with plenty of watchful eyes and UAPD around, this was a safe place to interact with anyone save a militant terrorist. Excluding people from the picnic wasn''t a matter of safety, it was class discrimination. If someone didn''t appear to meet the standard of being a middle class college student with a clean record, they were discriminated against.\n\nStudents at <a href="http://www.uakron.edu/" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a> don''t hear a lot about class discrimination in <a title="The City of Akron on Wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akron,_Ohio" target="_blank">Akron</a>. Class discrimination is something that students hear about in the news like<a title="Dalit Network" href="http://www.dalitnetwork.org/" target="_blank"> the caste system in India</a> or <a href="http://www.iheu.org/caste-discrimination-africa" target="_blank">Africa</a>, and the impression students get is that it doesn''t happen in the United States. The truth is that our community is made up of two distinct social classes. The edge of a college campus in an urban setting is a place where poverty and affluence meet. It is a place where class discrimination can very easily sneak in if we are not intentional about avoiding it.\n\nI''d like to see the University of Akron have a picnic for the community that doesn''t discriminate based on class. <a title="Article 27 of the UDHR" href="http://www.un.org/en/documents/udhr/index.shtml#a27" target="_blank">Article 27</a> of the <a title="UDHR" href="http://www.un.org/en/documents/udhr/" target="_blank">Universal Declaration of Human Rights</a> states that, "Everyone has the right freely to participate in the cultural life of the community." We should invite everyone who lives in the community, student or not, clean or dirty, rich or poor, criminal record or innocent, handicapped or healthy to be a part of our community picnics. Let''s come together with every member of our community and embrace them where they are. Some may be lower class than others, but each is a valuable human being and community member.', 'Class Discrimination', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '95-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:43', '2013-11-22 14:04:43', '', 95, 'http://josiahsprague.com/95-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(534, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:52', '2013-11-22 14:04:52', 'For a typical college student having fun is synonymous with drinking. I''m not against drinking or having fun while doing it, but since when is alcohol a prerequisite to having fun? I think as college students we''ve forgotten how to have fun.\n\nMy idea of having fun growing up was to have people over for a campfire in my backyard. When I came to college I jumped on the drinking bandwagon for awhile, but then I realized that I could have just as much fun at a campfire and I had made a lot more valuable memories at campfires than my fragmented memories from a night out drinking.\n\nThere''s plenty of places to drink on campus, and legal or not, students find a way to do it. But one of the drawbacks of living on campus is that there aren''t quite as many places to have a campfire.\n\nThis year at the Townhouses we''re changing that by hosting cookouts in our "Townhouse backyard" where "We grill out to chill out." Instead of asking people to B.Y.O.B.,  we started by asking people to B.Y.O.G. (the g is for grill). Our first cookout we had 75 people show up, prompting us to create the B.Y.O._ series. Our third B.Y.O._ event is coming up on October 14 at 6:06pm, and is going to be a fall-themed cookout with corn stalks, scarecrows, pumpkin pie, cider and pumpkin carving.\n\nEveryone on campus is invited. B.Y.O.P. (pumpkin),  and B.Y.O.F (food, friends, fall spirit),  and come join us for a good time!\n\nUpdate: You can find <a href="http://www.facebook.com/event.php?eid=153581136906" target="_blank">the Facebook event </a>by searching for "B.Y.O._ Round Three" on Facebook.', 'B.Y.O._ Round Three', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '85-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:52', '2013-11-22 14:04:52', '', 85, 'http://josiahsprague.com/85-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(535, 1, '2013-11-22 14:04:54', '2013-11-22 14:04:54', 'When I first got an email introducing a community picnic in<a title="University Park Alliance" href="http://www.upakron.com/" target="_blank"> the neighborhood south of campus</a>, something clicked for me;\n<blockquote>Good evening everyone!\n\nDue to a rise in crime in the areas south of Exchange Street over the past two weeks, we will be partnering up with our colleagues at the University to host a Community Zipnic on Thursday June 4th at 5:30p.m. located at Buchtel Field.\n\nPlease let me know if any of you will be able to attend/help out at the event.\n\nFree Food, Drinks (Beverages the 21 and older crowed as well!).  Tell your friends and other students that live in that area!\n\nAlso we will be going door to door in the area on Tuesday.\n\nThanks,\n\nJason E. Ziegler\n\nPresident, Associated Student Government</blockquote>\nI loved the idea of a picnic. It seemed like a perfect response to crime in the neighborhood. What better way to prevent crime than to build a sense of community, helping everyone feel included and involved in the lives of others in their community?\n\nAs soon as I got the email, I immediately began doing my part to make <a title="First Community Zipnic on Facebook" href="http://www.facebook.com/event.php?eid=86353743719" target="_blank">the first Community Zipnic</a> happen. I bought Facebook advertising on behalf of <a title="Associated Student Government" href="http://www.uakron.edu/groups/asg/" target="_blank">Associated Student Government</a>. I invited every one of my friends on the <a href="http://www.uakron.edu/reslife/" target="_blank">Residence Life &amp; Housing</a> staff and asked them to bring residents from their buildings. I invited all of my friends from <a href="http://www.campusfocus.org" target="_blank">Campus Focus</a> and encouraged them to come to the picnic and organize a game of Ultimate Frisbee and  I invited a few men that I had met on the streets of the neighborhood to join us and bring their friends.\n\nI arrived on the day of the picnic with high hopes. Buchtel Field was set up with everything to make a great picnic; blue and gold balloons, booths set up to talk with <a href="http://www3.uakron.edu/police/index.htm" target="_blank">The University of Akron Police (UAPD)</a> and Associated Student Government about safety, a row of tables filled with wonderful food from <a href="http://www.uakron.edu/aux/dining/" target="_blank">Dining Services</a>, Resident Assistants playing corn hole with their residents, a beer garden with free samples of <a href="http://www.roobrew.com" target="_blank">Roo Brew</a>, Campus Focus playing Ultimate Frisbee and others playing kickball. Attendance was over 300, and the food was gone well before the scheduled end time. It was a blowout sucess by appearances. But was it really?\n\nStill thinking about <a href="http://josiahsprague.wordpress.com/2009/09/28/picnics-parties-and-banquets/" target="_self">my post from the other day</a>. More coming later...', 'Community Zipnic', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '82-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:04:54', '2013-11-22 14:04:54', '', 82, 'http://josiahsprague.com/82-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(536, 1, '2013-11-22 14:05:05', '2013-11-22 14:05:05', 'Students at the University of Akron are getting excited about church. Campus Focus is the second largest student organization at the University of Akron and growing in size. While many churches are losing attendance from the college age crowd, Campus Focus is growing.\n\nMany college students imagine church is about old people wearing their Sunday best and singing hymns, but students at Campus Focus are interested in something different. Brian Kunkler, the pastor at Campus Focus, explains what Campus Focus is about to a group of students,\n<blockquote>The God that we follow around here has a bigger vision for your life than you have for your life. The God who lingers around here, whom we’re going to sing songs to in just a minute, has a bigger dream for your life than you have for your own life and He’s desperate to lead you in it. This is a high change environment.</blockquote>\nCampus Focus is a collection of college students, from many different backgrounds who have come together in the name of Jesus Christ. All are welcome, regardless of their current beliefs, gender, race, social status or lifestyle. But Brian concludes his speech to students with a warning;\n<blockquote>Look at what happened to people when they lingered around Jesus. Here’s a sampling from the four gospels. The blind see. The lame walk.  The oppressed set free. The outcasts are welcomed as family. The prostitutes become women of honor. The tax collectors become servants of the true king. Common fishermen become world changers. Swindlers and cheats pay back what they stole, and even get generous. The guilty get forgiven. The sin stain get cleansed. The proud get humbled and the self-righteous bow the knee. Wherever Jesus is, change is soon to follow.</blockquote>\nThe Campus Focus website, <a title="campusfocus.org" href="http://www.campusfocus.org" target="_blank">campusfocus.org </a>welcomes students to come to a weekly meeting at <a title="The Chapel in Akron" href="http://www.the-chapel.org" target="_blank">The Chapel in Akron</a> every Thursday night at 7:30 to see what they are all about. You can also find a weekly podcast from Campus Focus on the website.\n\nDISCLOSURE: Campus Focus is a student organization at <a title="The University of Akron" href="http://www.uakron.edu/" target="_blank">The University of Akron</a> of which I am an active participant. I was not paid to write this, however, it was written for a class that I am enrolled in this semester.', 'A High Change Environment', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '37-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:05:05', '2013-11-22 14:05:05', '', 37, 'http://josiahsprague.com/37-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(537, 1, '2013-11-22 14:06:26', '2013-11-22 14:06:26', 'Looking around on the internet, I''m finding some trends as far as what makes a website successful. This is my no means a definitive list, but rather a quick summary of some things that I am drawn to on the web and why I think these things are essential for a successful website. While many of my observations apply to websites in general, my specific focus will be on portfolio websites.\r\n<h2>Some Rules of Successful Design</h2>\r\nWhat makes a website successful is, first and foremost, it''s purpose. The purpose of a website is to communicate a message. The message needs to be clearly defined, and every aspect of the website should do it''s part to communicate that message. All of the aspects of a website are secondary to the message of the site.\r\n\r\nThe message of a portfolio website is, most likely, "Hire me!". This message should be made clear, and supported by the content of the site. A successful portfolio site will include examples of work to communicate the author''s skill, as well as a call to action encouraging visitors to consider hiring.\r\n\r\nSome supporting factors that make any website effective in communicating a message include; consistent navigation, usable search, standards compliance, up to date information and effective monetization.\r\n<h2>Some Things to Avoid</h2>\r\nIn light of a website''s message, anything that does not contribute to or enhance the message should be avoided. A feature may be a powerful communication tool on one website and completely out of place on another. For example, a discussion board may be a very useful tool on a social media website, but on a professional portfolio it may be out of place.\r\n\r\nOther things to avoid are unnecessary Flash animations, sounds that play automatically, and features that use large amounts of resources. These things can be used occasionally in the right places but to use them all the time is sort of like putting salt on everything you eat. Not everything needs it, and sometimes it''s better without.\r\n<h2>Good Examples</h2>\r\nThere is no shortage of good examples of portfolio websites.  DesignM.ag has a list of <a title="101 Awesome Portfolio Sites" href="http://designm.ag/inspiration/101-awesome-portfolio-sites/" target="_blank">101 Awesome Portfolio Sites.</a> The number one thing that I like about most of these portfolio sites is that they are standards compliant. It might not seem like a big deal, but standards compliance is the backbone of a successful site. Everything is built out of code, so if the code is healthy, it lends itself to a healthy site.\r\n\r\nThe first site on DesignM.ag''s list is <a title="Spoon Graphics" href="http://www.spoongraphics.co.uk/" target="_blank">Spoon Graphics</a>. Not only does the site look great, but it achieves its purpose effectively. The first thing a visitor to the site sees is the banner across the middle of the page explaining what the site is and offering links to find out more, view the portfolio or hire Chris, the owner of the site.\r\n\r\nAnother portfolio that stands out to me from the list is <a title="Design Disease" href="http://designdisease.com/" target="_blank">Design Disease</a>. The thing that draws me to this site is the creative design. The site incorporates an ocean theme while still maintaining a site that is easy to navigate. Design Disease also includes several other features that make it a successful portfolio including consistent navigation, usable search, standards compliance, up to date information and effective monetization.\r\n\r\nI especially like Design Disease''s natural approach to monetization. First by simply offering services for hire, but also by offering the services of other companies such as HostGator for web hosting. Many websites try to increase revenue by placing banner ads chosen by key word, but Design Disease simply makes a natural recommendation. Just as a side-note, this is where I see the future of advertising headed.\r\n<h2>Bad Examples</h2>\r\nPoorly designed portfolio sites are naturally harder to find, as they don''t get as much attention, but some of the worst of the worst can be found by doing a Google search for "worst website ever". There are some websites, which I generally dislike. These aren''t necessarily bad websites, but sites that I feel could do a much better job at communicating their message.\r\n\r\nHave a look at the introduction page on <a title="Scott Rockers'' Portfolio" href="http://rockerssoft.org/scott/" target="_blank">Scott Rockers'' Portfolio</a>. While I can appreciate the intent to make sure that visitors are aware that the site is Flash-based, the introduction page is an unnecessary step for most visitors that gets in the way of the message of the site. The best solution would be to avoid Flash unless it is absolutely necessary (most multimedia and animations can be handled with HTML, CSS and JavaScript these days). However, even when Flash is necessary the question of whether or not the visitor has Flash player installed can be addressed by the computer. Don''t make visitors do the work that your website should do for them. Include a script to skip the intro page if Flash is installed.\r\n\r\nOne last example is <a title="Eyes Go Dark" href="http://eyesgodark.com" target="_blank">Eyes Go Dark</a>. Eyes Go Dark is an example of a great message that is poorly communicated. When the site first loads, there is an introduction page with several external links. While external links are fine, it doesn''t make sense for them to be the first thing a visitor sees. That''s like visiting a house and being shown the way out as you enter. Skip the intro page and show visitors what they came for. Your message and your content should be right up front welcoming the visitors to your site.', 'Basic Principles of Website Design', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '36-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:06:26', '2013-11-22 14:06:26', '', 36, 'http://josiahsprague.com/36-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(680, 1, '2014-03-02 20:16:56', '2014-03-02 20:16:56', '<p>I’m a front-end web developer with varied background that includes mass media communication, design, writing.&nbsp;<span style="font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit;">Right now I</span><span style="font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit;">’m focusing my energy on WordPress development, but I love to learn new things.</span><span style="font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit;">&nbsp;I&nbsp;</span><span style="font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit;">live in a small mountain town of the Dominican Republic called Jarabacoa, and use this website to share my journey with people around the world.</span></p>\n<h2><span style="font-style: inherit; font-variant: inherit;">What’s Here?</span></h2>\n<p>I’ve decided to start over with a clean slate on my website, so there isn’t much here.</p>\n<ul>\n</ul>\n<p>You can&nbsp;<a href="http://eepurl.com/pWuUX" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push([''_trackEvent'',''outbound-article'',''http://eepurl.com'']);">subscribe to my personal updates via email</a>&nbsp;if you’d like.</p>\n<h2>Elsewhere…</h2>\n<p>Other places I’m active online;</p>\n<p>Twitter: <a href="http://twitter.com/jrswp" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push([''_trackEvent'',''outbound-article'',''http://twitter.com'']);">@jrswp</a></p>\n<p>Medium: <a href="https://medium.com/@jrswp" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push([''_trackEvent'',''outbound-article'',''http://medium.com'']);">@jrswp</a></p>\n<p>GitHub: <a href="https://github.com/josiahsprague" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push([''_trackEvent'',''outbound-article'',''http://github.com'']);">josiahsprague</a></p>\n<p></p>\n<blockquote></blockquote>', 'Hi, I''m Josiah Sprague', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '351-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-03-02 20:16:56', '2014-03-02 20:16:56', '', 351, 'http://josiahsprague.com/351-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(540, 1, '2013-07-15 21:40:58', '2013-07-15 21:40:58', 'I''m a web and video craftsman currently living in Jarabacoa in the Dominican Republic and working as the Media Coordinator at <a href="http://doulosdiscovery.org">Doulos Discovery School</a>.\r\n\r\nHere''s a quick summary of the stuff you''ll find here;\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong><a title="My Story" href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/story/">My Journal</a></strong> - Basically the story of my life; everything that I''m doing and learning. May or may not be interesting. For stalkers trying to keep tabs on me.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/dr/"><strong>Dominican Republic</strong></a> - Stories about life in the Dominican Republic, my work at Doulos, and everything related to that. <a title="Support" href="http://josiahsprague.com/support/">Support me!</a></p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/thinking/"><strong>Thoughts</strong></a> - Thoughts about current issues and events or things going on in my life. Often religious or humanitarian in nature.</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><strong><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/web/">Web Consultation</a></strong> - Free consultation and advice related to your website. Not much here yet. Stay tuned.</p>\r\nSide note: Get a deal on some great budget software; I started using You Need a Budget to keep track of my money. It''s really great. I highly recommend that you check it out. If you want to buy it, use my affiliate link, we''ll each get $6 out of it: <a href="http://ynab-coupon-code.com/">YNAB Coupon Code</a>.\r\n\r\nYou can <a href="http://eepurl.com/pWuUX">subscribe to my new posts via email</a> or add <a href="http://josiahsprague.com/feed/">my RSS feed</a> to your reader. I also have individual feeds for each of the categories listed above.\r\n<h2>My Values</h2>\r\nIf people only remember two things about my life, they should be this;\r\n<blockquote>I am a great sinner, and Christ is a great savior.</blockquote>\r\nMy take on religion;\r\n<blockquote>Love God. Love others. Nothing else matters.</blockquote>\r\nOn being nice;\r\n<blockquote>Love is something more splendid and stern than mere kindness.</blockquote>\r\nThe way I think;\r\n<blockquote>Everything that is alive is changing. People, organizations, ideas, all of it. What is static is dead.</blockquote>\r\nWhen it comes to the work I do;\r\n<blockquote>If I''m going to spend a day cutting down a tree, I''ll spend two thirds of it sharpening my axe.</blockquote>', 'Hi, I''m Josiah Sprague', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '351-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-07-15 21:40:58', '2013-07-15 21:40:58', '', 351, 'http://josiahsprague.com/351-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(544, 1, '2013-11-22 14:32:59', '2013-11-22 14:32:59', 'I''m a web craftsman currently living in Jarabacoa in the Dominican Republic teaching at <a href="http://doulosdiscovery.org">Doulos Discovery School</a> and building a web production company.\r\n\r\nIf you''d like to support my cause, take a look at my <a title="Support" href="http://josiahsprague.com/support/">support page</a>.\r\n\r\nIf you''re interested in web services that I can provide for you, fill out my <a title="Web Services Quote" href="http://josiahsprague.com/web-services-quote/">quote request form</a> for more information.\r\n\r\nIf you want to stay in the loop about what I''m doing, I''ve divided my blog into two categories;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/work/">Work and Ministry Updates</a> - Updates about my work and ministry as it evolves.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/personal/">Personal Updates</a> - Posts about my personal life, things that I am thinking about, often something I am learning.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nYou can also <a href="http://eepurl.com/pWuUX">subscribe to my updates via email</a> or <a href="http://josiahsprague.com/feed/">RSS</a>.\r\n<h2>My Values</h2>\r\nIf people only remember two things about my life, they should be this;\r\n<blockquote>I am a great sinner, and Christ is a great savior.</blockquote>\r\nMy take on religion;\r\n<blockquote>Love God. Love others. Nothing else matters.</blockquote>\r\nOn truth;\r\n<blockquote>"The truth is a relationship."\r\n\r\n<footer>— <cite><a title="The Pope on Twitter" href="https://twitter.com/pontifex">@Pontifex</a></cite></footer></blockquote>\r\nConcerning being nice;\r\n<blockquote>Love is something more splendid and stern than mere kindness.</blockquote>\r\nMy beliefs about change;\r\n<blockquote>Everything that is alive is changing. People, organizations, ideas, all of it. What is static is dead.</blockquote>\r\nWhen it comes to the work I do;\r\n<blockquote>If I''m going to spend a day cutting down a tree, I''ll spend two thirds of it sharpening my axe.</blockquote>', 'Hi, I''m Josiah Sprague', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '351-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 14:32:59', '2013-11-22 14:32:59', '', 351, 'http://josiahsprague.com/351-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
