(578, 1, '2014-01-13 14:21:17', '2014-01-13 14:21:17', '<h1>An Organic Connection Across Diverse Cultural Backgrounds</h1>\n\n<p>When I first started working with Doulos, it reminded me a lot of my high school, Cuyahoga Valley Christian Academy. Both are private Christian schools where the staff care deeply about the spiritual development of the students, and there is a strong culture of academic excellence that stands out from other schools. I sometimes feel that there is more in common between the culture of Doulos and CVCA than there is between CVCA and public schools in Ohio. But after spending a couple of years here I&#8217;ve begun to realize that there are also many cultural differences, and I long for the students here to learn and expand their view of the world and to be able to understand the values of my home culture.</p>\n\n<p>That&#8217;s why I am so excited about a new exchange student partnership between Doulos and CVCA. It began this past semester with two CVCA students who came to study for a semester here at Doulos. I was so proud to have students here representing my alma mater (and they represented it very well). This semester, I am thrilled that two Doulos students have the opportunity to represent their school as exchange students at CVCA. </p>\n\n<p>One of those students happens to be one of the first students I met when I came to visit Doulos with a team in April 2012. We were visiting homes of Dominican Doulos staff and no one on our team knew Spanish, so Darina came with us to translate. It is very exciting for me that a student who played a key role in introducing me to Dominican culture now has the opportunity to experience my home culture at the same high school I attended.</p>\n\n<p>You might assume that the connection between Doulos and CVCA came about because of an intentional effort on my part, or on the part of the Danae LeMoine (another Doulos staff member who attended high school at CVCA), but that isn&#8217;t the case. The exchange program, and Danae and myself being here, all came about completely separately. It was as if God was working all three together without awareness on our part. </p>\n\n<p>It is exciting to see how God works in ways that we don&#8217;t expect or plan for, interweaving cultures and experiences within his diverse Church. My hope is that through this partnership between Doulos and CVCA that more and more people would see and celebrate that beautiful connection that we have in Christ regardless of our culture and background, and that it would enable us to value and love each other more deeply across those boundaries.</p>', 'An Organic Connection Across Diverse Cultural Backgrounds', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '577-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-01-13 14:21:17', '2014-01-13 14:21:17', '', 577, 'http://josiahsprague.com/577-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(548, 1, '2013-11-25 19:49:34', '2013-11-25 19:49:34', '<h2>Do One Thing Really Well</h2>\r\nLately, it seems like there is never enough time in the day to do all the things on my plate. Between producing media for Doulos, teaching class, blogging, translating, attending study groups, making websites, building a small business on the side and trying to keep my education up to date, I do a lot of things. But lately I''ve been dissatisfied; My work is mediocre by my own standards and I''m not accomplishing things that are meaningful to me.\r\n\r\nI want to do better work. I want to do more meaningful things. I want to use my talents more fully. I want to love people better and build deeper relationships. I want to have time to reflect on what I''m doing. I want to use the one life that I have to its maximum potential.\r\n\r\nI need to focus my energy on doing one thing really well rather doing many things with mediocrity. After spending time reflecting on my values and passions, I''ve clarified my personal vocation, my "one thing", as the following;\r\n<blockquote>Helping individuals and organizations <a href="http://bible.com/100/gal.5.13-14.nasb">serve one another</a> via the web.</blockquote>\r\nMy current challenge is bring all the aspects of my life keenly into focus on that vocation, and to gracefully say "no" to anything that doesn''t contribute to it. Rather than focus on the negatives of the things that are distracting me from my vocation, the rest of this post is a glimpse of the positive ways that I am beginning to focus all of my time and energy towards it.\r\n\r\nI envision helping people and organizations serve one another in two ways. The first is through <strong>craftsmanship</strong>, and the second is through <strong>apprenticeship</strong>.\r\n<h2>Craftsmanship</h2>\r\n<em>Craftsmanship means using one''s gifts and talents to skillfully create high quality work and design.</em> My vision is to form a business that will craft high quality websites for a variety of clients and help them cultivate a valuable web presence that will help them serve their target audience.\r\n\r\nI have already established a small base of six initial clients for this company. And while I am very familiar with my craft, I have a lot to learn about running a business, so I am working with <a href="http://www.fourthwater.org/">Fourth Water</a>, a local business accelerator in Jarabacoa, and developing a formal business plan.\r\n<h2>Apprenticeship</h2>\r\nThe word "apprenticeship" is related to the Spanish word "aprender" (to learn) and<em> it means learning via practical experience from a skilled professional.</em> I believe that apprenticeship is vital to quality work and craftsmanship, and that professionals must constantly be apprentices as well as mentors. My vision is that my role as a  professional would become more and more aligned with my role as a teacher.\r\n\r\nThis past semester I had the opportunity to teach an elective communication class at Doulos. This coming semester, inspired by my passion for craftsmanship on the web and by students requesting to learn computer programming, I am developing plans to teach <a href="https://www.khanacademy.org/cs">a programming elective</a> for high school and a <a href="http://codeclubworld.org/">code club</a> for elementary school. My long term vision is to be able to connect these students with opportunities to learn and develop their skills via hands on experiences with the business that I am forming.\r\n<h2>A Work in Progress</h2>\r\nThe specifics of this vision are still forming, and there is a long way to go. My desire is that they will continue to become clearer and more focused and that the end result will be a fruitful investment of my time and talents. I will continue to post updates here as things evolve, and I expect to spend a lot of time over the holidays developing and refining a plan.', 'Focusing My Vision', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'focusing-my-vision', '', '\nhttp://josiahsprague.com/contact/', '2014-04-04 20:43:57', '2014-04-04 20:43:57', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.com/?p=548', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(551, 1, '2013-11-22 19:54:56', '2013-11-22 19:54:56', '<p>Lately, it seems like there is never enough time in the day to do all of the things on my plate. Between producing media for Doulos, teaching class, blogging, translating, attending several small groups, making websites, building a small business on the side and trying to keep my education up to date, I do a lot of things. But my results are mediocre by my own measurement and I''m not accomplishing things that are meaningful to me.</p>\n\n<p>I want to use the one life that I have to it''s maximum potential. I want to accomplish more. I want to do better work. I want to use my talents more fully. I want to love people better and build deeper relationships.</p>\n\n<p>After a lot of reflection, I''ve realized that in order to do more, I need to do less. Or rather, I need to focus my energy on doing one thing well rather doing many things with mediocrity.</p>\n', 'Do One Thing Really Well', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '548-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-22 19:54:56', '2013-11-22 19:54:56', '', 548, 'http://josiahsprague.com/548-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(554, 1, '2013-11-25 16:01:22', '2013-11-25 16:01:22', '<p>Lately, it seems like there is never enough time in the day to do all of the things on my plate. Between producing media for Doulos, teaching class, blogging, translating, attending several small groups, making websites, building a small business on the side and trying to keep my education up to date, I do a lot of things. But lately I''ve been dissatisfied; My work is mediocre by my own standards and I''m not accomplishing things that are meaningful to me.</p>\n\n<p>I want to do better work. I want to accomplish more meaningful things. I want to use my talents more fully. I want to love people better and build deeper relationships. I want to have time to reflect on what I''m doing. I want to use the one life that God has given me to it''s maximum potential.</p>\n\n<p>I need to focus my energy on doing one thing well rather doing many things with mediocrity. After spending time reflecting on my values and passions, I''ve clarified my personal vocation or calling as the following;</p>\n\n<p>Helping individuals and organizations serve one another via the web.</p>\n\n<p>My current challenge is bring all of the aspects of my life keenly into focus on that calling. My ideal career involves two parts. The first is craftsmanship, and the second is apprenticeship. My vision is a work in progress, but I want to share with you how I see those parts playing out in my near future.</p>\n\n<p>Craftsmanship\nCraftsmanship means using one''s gifts and talents to skillfully create high quality work and design. My vision is to form a business that will craft high quality websites for a variety of clients and to cultivate and increase the market value of those individuals and organizations via the web medium.</p>\n\n<p>I have already established a small base of six initial clients for this company. While I am very familiar with my craft, I have a lot to learn concerning running a business, so I am currently working with Fourth Water, a local business accelerator in Jarabacoa, and developing a formal business plan.</p>\n\n<p>Apprenticeship\nThe word "apprenticeship" is related to the Spanish word "aprender--to learn" and it means learning via practical experience from a skilled professional. I believe that both being an apprentice and having apprentices is vital to quality work and craftsmanship. My vision is to merge my role as a constantly learning professional with my role as a teacher.</p>\n\n<p>This past semester I had an opportunity to have a formal role teaching an elective communication class at Doulos Discovery School in Jarabacoa. This coming semester, inspired by my passion for the web and student requests to learn computer programming, I am exploring the possibility of teaching a programming elective for high school and a code club for elementary school. My long term vision is to be able to connect these students with hands on experiences to learn via the business that I am forming.</p>\n\n<p>The specifics of this vision are still forming, and there is a long way to go. My desire is that they will continue to become clearer and more focused and that the end result will be a fruitful investment of my time and energy. I covet your advice, prayers and continued support while I explore this vision.</p>\n', 'Focusing My Vision and Calling', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '548-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-25 16:01:22', '2013-11-25 16:01:22', '', 548, 'http://josiahsprague.com/548-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
