(585, 1, '2014-02-15 18:28:22', '2014-02-15 18:28:22', 'I''m a web craftsman currently living in Jarabacoa in the Dominican Republic teaching at <a href="http://doulosdiscovery.org">Doulos Discovery School</a> and building a web production company.\r\n\r\nIf you''d like to support my cause, take a look at my <a title="Support" href="http://josiahsprague.com/support/">support page</a>.\r\n\r\nIf you''re interested in web services that I can provide for you, fill out my <a title="Web Services Quote" href="http://josiahsprague.com/web-services-quote/">quote request form</a> for more information.\r\n\r\nIf you want to stay in the loop about what I''m doing, I''ve divided my blog into two categories;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/work/">Work Updates</a> - Updates about my work and career. Generally of public interest.</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://josiahsprague.com/category/personal/">Personal Updates</a> - Posts about my personal life, things that I am thinking about, often something I am learning. Probably only interesting if we''re friends IRL.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nYou can also <a href="http://eepurl.com/pWuUX">subscribe to my updates via email</a> or <a href="http://josiahsprague.com/feed/">RSS</a>.\r\n<h2>My Values</h2>\r\nIf people only remember two things about my life, they should be this;\r\n<blockquote>I am a great sinner, and Christ is a great savior.</blockquote>\r\nMy take on religion;\r\n<blockquote>Love God. Love others. Nothing else matters.</blockquote>\r\nOn truth;\r\n<blockquote>"The truth is a relationship."\r\n\r\n<footer>— <cite><a title="The Pope on Twitter" href="https://twitter.com/pontifex">@Pontifex</a></cite></footer></blockquote>\r\nConcerning being nice;\r\n<blockquote>Love is something more splendid and stern than mere kindness.</blockquote>\r\nMy beliefs about change;\r\n<blockquote>Everything that is alive is changing. People, organizations, ideas, all of it. What is static is dead.</blockquote>\r\nWhen it comes to the work I do;\r\n<blockquote>If I''m going to spend a day cutting down a tree, I''ll spend two thirds of it sharpening my axe.</blockquote>', 'Hi, I''m Josiah Sprague', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '351-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-15 18:28:22', '2014-02-15 18:28:22', '', 351, 'http://josiahsprague.com/351-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(582, 1, '2014-01-13 14:25:19', '2014-01-13 14:25:19', 'When I first started working with Doulos, it reminded me a lot of my high school, Cuyahoga Valley Christian Academy. Both are private Christian schools where the staff care deeply about the spiritual development of the students, and there is a strong culture of academic excellence that stands out from other schools. I sometimes feel that there is more in common between the culture of Doulos and CVCA than there is between CVCA and public schools in Ohio. But after spending a couple of years here I’ve begun to realize that there are also many cultural differences, and I long for the students here to learn and expand their view of the world and to be able to understand the values of my home culture.\r\n\r\nThat’s why I am so excited about <a href="http://doulosdiscovery.org/launching-exciting-new-exchange-student-partnership/">a new exchange student partnership between Doulos and CVCA</a>. It began this past semester with two CVCA students who came to study for a semester here at Doulos. I was so proud to have students here representing my alma mater (and they represented it very well). This semester, I am thrilled that two Doulos students have the opportunity to represent their school as exchange students at CVCA.\r\n\r\nOne of those students happens to be one of the first students I met when I came to visit Doulos with a team in April 2012. We were visiting homes of Dominican Doulos staff and no one on our team knew Spanish, so Darina came with us to translate. It is very exciting for me that a student who played a key role in introducing me to Dominican culture now has the opportunity to experience my home culture at the same high school I attended.\r\n\r\nYou might assume that the connection between Doulos and CVCA came about because of an intentional effort on my part, or on the part of the Danae LeMoine (another Doulos staff member who attended high school at CVCA), but that isn’t the case. The exchange program, and Danae and myself being here, all came about completely separately. It was as if God was working all three together without awareness on our part.\r\n\r\nIt is exciting to see how God works in ways that we don’t expect or plan for, interweaving cultures and experiences within his diverse Church. My hope is that through this partnership between Doulos and CVCA that more and more people would see and celebrate that beautiful connection that we have in Christ regardless of our culture and background, and that it would enable us to value and love each other more deeply across those boundaries.', 'An Organic Connection Across Diverse Cultural Backgrounds', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '577-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-01-13 14:25:19', '2014-01-13 14:25:19', '', 577, 'http://josiahsprague.com/577-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
