(749, 1, '2014-03-10 18:51:39', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Christian Discipleship\n\nWe are disciples of Jesus Christ. That means following Him, being His “apprentice,” and learning to live out of a heart, mind and soul completely devoted to our Triune God. We seek to exalt Christ at every turn, teaching students how to be His disciples in every aspect of life, including the academic subjects. In those academic classes, we seek to be a Biblically Integrated school, holding fast to God’s word and teaching each class from the perspective that God is the foundation for all truth, and that anything we can study in His creation can only be well known if we know our Creator well.\n\n<span style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 28.8px;"> </span>\n\nExpeditionary Learning\n\nWe use project-based learning expeditions that encourage high levels of student engagement, achievement, and character development. The value of expeditionary learning is that learning and leadership cannot be fully grasped in a traditional educational setting. We (our whole staff, not just students) take learning into our own hands and encourage each other to take supervised and calculated risks, to try, fail, and try again, and learn intangibles like teamwork, overcoming adversity, pushing oneself physically, and simply doing hard things. We inspire our students to be engaged and self-motivated learners by fostering students’ learning through fieldwork, experts, and product creation.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCalling Prep (College Prep)\n\nWe view higher education as a tool to equip students to live out their calling as disciples of Christ and develop the vocation to which God has called them. We prepare students academically, socially, and spiritually to attend college internationally. Our desire is for students to be academically, socially, and spiritually equipped for higher education at an institution of their choosing.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMixed Economic Student Body\n\nWe believe that leaders come from all economic backgrounds. In a country where people are often isolated from each other based on their families’ income levels, we attempt to bridge the gap by educating rich and poor together and building lasting relationships between socioeconomic classes by reserving half of our enrollment for full tuition-paying students and the other half for Christian families who prepare their children spiritually but are not able to provide for their academic needs.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDominican\n\nDoulos is located in the town of Jarabacoa in the mountains of the Dominican Republic. We meet the standards of the Dominican Ministry of Education for international schools. We seek to honor local traditions, engage local leadership, and prepare our students to lead and impact within the country. Our school mascot is “the revolutionary,” and our desire is to see our students complete their post high school education internationally and then return to the Dominican Republic to take on revolutionary roles in the leadership of the country.', '', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2014-03-10 18:51:39', '2014-03-10 18:51:39', '', 0, 'http://josiahsprague.com/?p=749', 0, 'post', '', 0),
